WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.520 --> 00:00:13.120
In the year 1812,
a Swiss explorer and eccentric named

00:00:13.120 --> 00:00:17.600
Johann Ludwig Burckhardt was travelling in
the Middle East,

00:00:17.600 --> 00:00:21.840
in the region of what is today Jordan.

00:00:22.480 --> 00:00:27.039
Burckhardt was a strange and colorful
character.

00:00:27.039 --> 00:00:32.800
Born on the shores of Lake Geneva, he had
traveled to England to study, and there

00:00:32.800 --> 00:00:38.239
had been employed by a group known as
the African Association, a gathering of

00:00:38.239 --> 00:00:44.079
upper-class Englishmen who financed
expeditions of exploration.

00:00:44.079 --> 00:00:49.280
They had given Burckhardt the task of
crossing the Sahara Desert from Cairo

00:00:49.280 --> 00:00:53.920
and making contact with what was then
considered a lost city,

00:00:53.920 --> 00:01:00.559
the city of Timbuktu.
Burckhardt took his assignment seriously,

00:01:00.559 --> 00:01:06.320
and he threw himself into it with all
the energy of a true Georgian eccentric.

00:01:06.320 --> 00:01:11.200
He began to study Arabic at Cambridge
University, and while there he began

00:01:11.200 --> 00:01:16.799
dressing in traditional Arab clothing,
wearing long, white dishdashas and a

00:01:16.799 --> 00:01:21.840
turban, much to the bemusement of his
fellow students.

00:01:21.840 --> 00:01:27.040
After graduating, he moved to Syria and
spent two years there practicing his

00:01:27.040 --> 00:01:33.040
Arabic, even adopting the name
Sheikh Ibrahim Ibn Abdallah, and attempting to

00:01:33.040 --> 00:01:39.280
pass himself off as a Muslim.
It's not clear how successful Burckhardt's

00:01:39.280 --> 00:01:44.960
disguise really was or whether anyone in
the Arab world was fooled.

00:01:44.960 --> 00:01:50.079
In preparation for his great journey, he
set out on a number of expeditions into

00:01:50.079 --> 00:01:54.960
the Syrian Desert, but many of these
ended in disaster.

00:01:54.960 --> 00:02:00.399
He was robbed on a number of occasions,
often by the same people he had hired to

00:02:00.399 --> 00:02:06.159
act as security on the journey.  But his
desire for adventure was unabated by

00:02:06.159 --> 00:02:13.040
these setbacks, and in 1812 he set out on
the journey from Syria to Cairo with the

00:02:13.040 --> 00:02:20.480
intention there of securing passage
across the great sandy sea of the Sahara.

00:02:20.480 --> 00:02:25.360
It was on this journey, taking the more
dangerous inland route through the

00:02:25.360 --> 00:02:30.560
baking summer heat of the desert, that
Burckhardt would make quite a different

00:02:30.560 --> 00:02:35.360
discovery.
It was here that his guides told him of

00:02:35.360 --> 00:02:41.840
a series of mysterious ruins hidden in a
narrow valley nearby which was known by

00:02:41.840 --> 00:02:48.000
locals as Wadi Mousa, or the Valley of
Moses.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:52.800
At this point, Burckhardt was still in
disguise as an Arab,

00:02:52.800 --> 00:02:56.800
and he contrived an excuse to visit the
ruins,

00:02:56.800 --> 00:03:03.440
as he writes in his diary.
August 22nd, 1812;

00:03:03.440 --> 00:03:07.519
I was particularly desirous of visiting
Moses' Valley,

00:03:07.519 --> 00:03:12.239
the antiquities of which I had heard the
country people speak in terms of great

00:03:12.239 --> 00:03:16.480
admiration.
I hired a guide at Eldjy to conduct me

00:03:16.480 --> 00:03:20.239
there, and paid him with a pair of old
horseshoes.

00:03:20.239 --> 00:03:24.400
He carried the goat and gave me a skin
of water to carry, as he knew that there

00:03:24.400 --> 00:03:30.720
was no water in the valley below.
As Burckhardt traveled with his guide

00:03:30.720 --> 00:03:36.560
down into the dry valley, he began to
feel increasingly fearful that someone

00:03:36.560 --> 00:03:42.000
would see through his disguise and his
ruse would be discovered.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:47.920
In following the rivulet of Eldjy westwards,
the valley soon narrows again, and it is

00:03:47.920 --> 00:03:51.360
here that the antiquities of Wadi Mousa
begin.

00:03:51.360 --> 00:03:56.319
Of these, I regret I am not able to give
a very complete account, but I knew well

00:03:56.319 --> 00:04:00.799
the character of the people around me.
I was without protection in the midst of

00:04:00.799 --> 00:04:04.159
a desert where no traveller had ever
before been seen,

00:04:04.159 --> 00:04:08.480
and a close examination of these works
of the infidels, as they are called, would

00:04:08.480 --> 00:04:13.200
have excited suspicions that I was a
magician in search of treasures. Future

00:04:13.200 --> 00:04:17.759
travelers may visit the spot under the
protection of an armed force, and the

00:04:17.759 --> 00:04:23.199
antiquities of Wadi Mousa will then be
found to rank amongst the most curious

00:04:23.199 --> 00:04:29.280
remains of ancient art.
Burckhardt's guides led him towards what

00:04:29.280 --> 00:04:35.680
from a distance appeared to be a sheer
cliff of brilliant red sandstone. But as

00:04:35.680 --> 00:04:41.840
he drew closer, he saw a well-concealed
ravine opening up in the stone wall, from

00:04:41.840 --> 00:04:48.880
which a sparse stream was flowing.
The valley seemed to be entirely closed

00:04:48.880 --> 00:04:55.840
by high rocks, but upon a nearer approach
I perceived a chasm about 15 or 20 feet

00:04:55.840 --> 00:05:00.880
in breadth, through which the rivulet
flows westward in winter.

00:05:00.880 --> 00:05:05.840
The precipices on either side of the
torrent are about 80 feet in height.

00:05:05.840 --> 00:05:10.400
In many places, the opening between them
at the top is less than at the bottom,

00:05:10.400 --> 00:05:14.880
and the sky is not visible from below.

00:05:15.360 --> 00:05:21.280
As Burckhardt traveled down this shady
chasm, his sense of excitement gradually

00:05:21.280 --> 00:05:26.880
grew to wonder as he came upon the sight
of an enormous tomb

00:05:26.880 --> 00:05:33.280
carved into the very rock of the red
sandstone mass around him.

00:05:33.280 --> 00:05:39.280
In continuing along the winding passage,
an excavated mausoleum came in view,

00:05:39.280 --> 00:05:44.400
the situation and beauty of which are
calculated to make an extraordinary

00:05:44.400 --> 00:05:49.039
impression upon the traveler, after
having traversed for nearly half an hour

00:05:49.039 --> 00:05:54.639
such a gloomy and almost subterraneous
passage as I have described.

00:05:54.639 --> 00:06:00.000
The natives call this monument Kaszr
Faraoun, or Pharaoh's Castle,

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:03.280
and pretend that it was the residence of
a prince.

00:06:03.280 --> 00:06:06.639
But it was rather the sepulcher of a
prince,

00:06:06.639 --> 00:06:11.120
and great must have been the opulence of
a city which could dedicate such

00:06:11.120 --> 00:06:17.280
monuments to the memory of its rulers.
It's clear that the sight of this hidden

00:06:17.280 --> 00:06:22.880
wonder had an enormous effect on
Burckhardt, and he writes breathlessly in

00:06:22.880 --> 00:06:28.639
his diary about the sight of this
enormous edifice.

00:06:28.639 --> 00:06:34.960
It is one of the most elegant remains of
antiquity existing in Syria. Its state of

00:06:34.960 --> 00:06:39.600
preservation resembles that of a
building recently finished, and on closer

00:06:39.600 --> 00:06:44.319
examination, I found it to be a work of
immense labor.

00:06:44.319 --> 00:06:49.840
The colonnade is about 35 feet high and
the columns are about three feet in

00:06:49.840 --> 00:06:55.360
diameter, with Corinthian capitals.
The colonnade is crowned with a pediment

00:06:55.360 --> 00:07:00.639
which consisted of an insulated cylinder
crowned with a vase, standing between two

00:07:00.639 --> 00:07:06.240
other structures in the shape of small
temples supported by short pillars.

00:07:06.240 --> 00:07:10.880
The entire front, from the base of the
columns to the top of the ornaments, may

00:07:10.880 --> 00:07:18.479
be 60 or 65 feet.
Johann Burckhardt would be the first

00:07:18.479 --> 00:07:24.160
European in modern times to set foot in
a city that for much of the previous

00:07:24.160 --> 00:07:32.000
millennium had been only a legend.
This was the ancient city of Petra.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:37.199
For centuries, it had been the heart of a
powerful trading kingdom that controlled

00:07:37.199 --> 00:07:42.720
the flow of spice and incense coming
across the desert from the lands of the

00:07:42.720 --> 00:07:47.039
east.
Its people had built vast constructions

00:07:47.039 --> 00:07:53.039
carved with immaculate skill into the
sandstone bedrock of the desert itself,

00:07:53.039 --> 00:07:59.039
and tamed one of the harshest
environments to be found on planet earth.

00:07:59.039 --> 00:08:05.360
They had fought and traded with empires
and played a starring role in many of

00:08:05.360 --> 00:08:12.720
the historical dramas of their age.
They were called the Nabataeans.

00:08:12.720 --> 00:08:18.240
As Burckhardt wandered through the gullies
and chasms of that lost city, he must

00:08:18.240 --> 00:08:23.599
have wondered how such a society had
flourished out here in the harsh

00:08:23.599 --> 00:08:29.280
landscape of the Arabian Desert.
If so great a civilization had

00:08:29.280 --> 00:08:35.760
arisen here, what had happened to empty
its temples and streets and leave it to

00:08:35.760 --> 00:08:41.839
be buried in the wandering sands of the
desert?

00:09:12.560 --> 00:09:17.120
My name's Paul Cooper, and you're
listening to The Fall of Civilizations

00:09:17.120 --> 00:09:21.440
Podcast.
Each episode, I look at a civilization of

00:09:21.440 --> 00:09:27.200
the past that rose to glory and then
collapsed into the ashes of history.

00:09:27.200 --> 00:09:32.480
I want to ask, what did they have in common?
What led to their fall? And what did it

00:09:32.480 --> 00:09:37.600
feel like to be a person alive at the
time who witnessed the end of their

00:09:37.600 --> 00:09:41.120
world?
In this episode, I want to look at one of

00:09:41.120 --> 00:09:46.080
the most remarkable stories of
civilizational survival to come down to

00:09:46.080 --> 00:09:50.640
us from the ancient world,
the story of the trading empire of the

00:09:50.640 --> 00:09:55.120
Nabataeans.
I want to explore how these once humble

00:09:55.120 --> 00:10:02.480
traders rose to become masters of the
desert sands and to defy empires.

00:10:02.480 --> 00:10:07.680
I want to show how the city of Petra
flourished to become the crossroads of

00:10:07.680 --> 00:10:11.600
the world,
and I want to explore what happened to

00:10:11.600 --> 00:10:17.320
finally bring down the empire of
Nabataea.

00:10:25.920 --> 00:10:33.120
Sandstone is a sedimentary rock.
It's formed when layers of sand are

00:10:33.120 --> 00:10:39.839
piled one upon another, and then over
time subjected to enormous pressure.

00:10:39.839 --> 00:10:45.760
This pressure, along with natural mineral
processes, fuses the sand grains together

00:10:45.760 --> 00:10:50.320
into rock.
Beneath the lands of Jordan, where this

00:10:50.320 --> 00:10:57.360
historical drama will unfold,
two great beds of sandstone stretch out.

00:10:57.360 --> 00:11:04.560
These are known as Disi sandstone
and Umm Ishrin sandstone.

00:11:04.720 --> 00:11:09.760
Disi sandstone is the youngest and
uppermost layer.

00:11:09.760 --> 00:11:14.959
Sandstones can be any colour depending
on the kinds of grains that went into

00:11:14.959 --> 00:11:20.800
forming it, and this kind is hard, pale
grey, and usually erodes to form

00:11:20.800 --> 00:11:26.480
distinctive dome-like structures.
But beneath this layer is a layer of

00:11:26.480 --> 00:11:30.880
older sandstone, at least 20 million
years older.

00:11:30.880 --> 00:11:36.480
This is Umm Ishrin sandstone,
and it's easily recognizable by the

00:11:36.480 --> 00:11:42.320
beautiful patterns it forms.
Due to its composition of iron,

00:11:42.320 --> 00:11:47.600
hydroxides, and manganese oxides, it is
famous for its colour,

00:11:47.600 --> 00:11:54.880
woven with rich oranges, purples,
and deep, rosy reds.

00:11:54.880 --> 00:12:00.560
The winding, interlaced patterns on these
stones were formed by the shapes of

00:12:00.560 --> 00:12:07.120
riverbeds that ran across this landscape
as much as 500 million years ago,

00:12:07.120 --> 00:12:11.040
in the middle of the period known as the
Cambrian.

00:12:11.040 --> 00:12:15.279
During this period, the planet earth
would have looked like a very alien

00:12:15.279 --> 00:12:19.920
place, almost like the surface of another
planet.

00:12:19.920 --> 00:12:26.880
There were a few plants like mosses and
lichens, but no leaves or trees, and no

00:12:26.880 --> 00:12:33.200
animals on the bare, rocky land.
The sea levels were high, with little or

00:12:33.200 --> 00:12:38.959
no polar ice, and so, large areas of the
continents were flooded with warm,

00:12:38.959 --> 00:12:42.800
shallow seas
filled with some of the largest forms of

00:12:42.800 --> 00:12:50.399
life to yet have evolved; crustaceans and
arthropods like trilobites.

00:12:50.399 --> 00:12:55.519
Over the hundreds of millions of years
that followed, an enormous amount of sand

00:12:55.519 --> 00:13:00.800
was deposited on the floors of these
oceans as their waves ground away at the

00:13:00.800 --> 00:13:07.360
rocks of the planet crust, as rainwaters
flowed down through rivers, bringing silt

00:13:07.360 --> 00:13:14.079
and dust along with them.
Today, the Umm Ishrin layer of sandstone

00:13:14.079 --> 00:13:19.440
is more than half a kilometer thick,
and in most places, it is buried by

00:13:19.440 --> 00:13:25.920
sheets of younger grey limestone.
This rosy sandstone would have remained

00:13:25.920 --> 00:13:32.480
buried if it weren't for the unique
plate tectonics of the Arabian Peninsula.

00:13:32.480 --> 00:13:37.360
The Arabian Plate is currently being
crushed by the other plates around it,

00:13:37.360 --> 00:13:41.279
the much larger African and Eurasian
Plates.

00:13:41.279 --> 00:13:45.920
It's being pushed north at a rate of 15
millimeters a year,

00:13:45.920 --> 00:13:49.199
or about as fast as your fingernails
grow.

00:13:49.199 --> 00:13:54.560
As it does so, these enormous forces have
thrown up mountain ranges in Turkey,

00:13:54.560 --> 00:13:59.440
Syria, and Iran,
and this vice-like pressure has caused

00:13:59.440 --> 00:14:04.800
the land mass to tilt.
All of the rock layers in Jordan now

00:14:04.800 --> 00:14:10.880
slope gently towards the northeast. The
upper limestone layer became exposed to

00:14:10.880 --> 00:14:19.600
the powerful forces of the wind and sand.
In places like Wadi Rum, Dana, the eastern

00:14:19.600 --> 00:14:23.680
shore of the Dead Sea, and at the site of
Petra,

00:14:23.680 --> 00:14:30.240
these grey sandstones eroded away,
and the long-buried layers of Umm Ishrin

00:14:30.240 --> 00:14:36.160
sandstone came into view in all their
rich, red glory.

00:14:36.160 --> 00:14:41.600
It's here in this landscape of rosy
red stone that the story of the

00:14:41.600 --> 00:14:45.800
Nabataeans would begin.

00:14:50.959 --> 00:14:56.079
The earliest hints of a people who may
have been the Nabataeans comes from the

00:14:56.079 --> 00:15:02.880
sources of the late kings of Assyria in
the 8th and 7th centuries BC.

00:15:02.880 --> 00:15:08.160
Like many rulers of this region before
them, they had struggled to control the

00:15:08.160 --> 00:15:13.360
nomadic tribal peoples living in the
deserts to their south.

00:15:13.360 --> 00:15:18.399
The 7th century BC Assyrian king
Sennacherib wrote the following

00:15:18.399 --> 00:15:24.000
inscription detailing one of his
campaigns in the south.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:28.000
In my first campaign,
I accomplished the defeat of Merodach-

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:34.320
-Baladan, King of Babylonia, together with
the army of Elam, his ally in the plain

00:15:34.320 --> 00:15:41.199
of Kish. On
my return march, the Tumuna, the Ubudu, the

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:47.680
Damunu, the Nabatu, who were not submissive at
all, all of them I conquered.

00:15:47.680 --> 00:15:53.440
Sennacherib's grandson, the king
Ashurbanipal, also wrote of encountering

00:15:53.440 --> 00:15:56.800
these desert peoples.

00:15:56.959 --> 00:16:02.160
The Nabatu live in a far-off desert
place where there are no wild animals,

00:16:02.160 --> 00:16:06.480
and not even birds build their nests.

00:16:07.279 --> 00:16:12.160
Today, many scholars dismiss the
similarities between the name of the

00:16:12.160 --> 00:16:18.320
ancient Nabatu and the later Nabataeans
as a simple coincidence.

00:16:18.320 --> 00:16:23.279
But what we do know is that since the
earliest history of this region, people

00:16:23.279 --> 00:16:29.360
have lived in this kind of nomadic
manner in the deserts of Arabia.

00:16:29.360 --> 00:16:36.160
These people would have no fixed towns
or cities, no houses or temples, but they

00:16:36.160 --> 00:16:42.000
would move with their herds, constructing
tents wherever they went, and moving as

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:47.759
restlessly as the desert sands.
They would survive by raising animals

00:16:47.759 --> 00:16:54.480
like goats, sheep, and cows, which could
provide meat, milk, and wool.

00:16:54.480 --> 00:16:58.720
They would forage and hunt what they
could from the environment, and would

00:16:58.720 --> 00:17:03.920
perhaps plant orchards that they would
return to each year on their wandering

00:17:03.920 --> 00:17:08.880
routes.
It seems that during their early history,

00:17:08.880 --> 00:17:13.760
the Nabataeans would also act as pirates
and bandits,

00:17:13.760 --> 00:17:18.559
using their knowledge of the desert to
outmaneuver the slow-moving trade

00:17:18.559 --> 00:17:23.600
caravans that passed through their
territory and along their coast.

00:17:23.600 --> 00:17:28.960
The first century Roman writer Strabo
recounts that the Nabataeans even

00:17:28.960 --> 00:17:35.360
dabbled in seaborne piracy.
Nabataea is a country with a large

00:17:35.360 --> 00:17:38.799
population and well-supplied with
pasturage.

00:17:38.799 --> 00:17:42.720
They also dwell on islands situated off
the coast nearby,

00:17:42.720 --> 00:17:47.600
and these Nabataeans formally lived a
peaceful life,

00:17:47.600 --> 00:17:52.960
but later, by means of rafts, went to
plundering the vessels of people sailing

00:17:52.960 --> 00:17:56.880
from Egypt,
but they paid the penalty when a fleet

00:17:56.880 --> 00:18:01.840
went over
and sacked their country.

00:18:03.360 --> 00:18:08.400
Soon, it seems that the Nabataeans
discovered that it was more profitable

00:18:08.400 --> 00:18:12.799
not to rob the trade caravans but to
offer them protection to pass through

00:18:12.799 --> 00:18:18.240
their territory for a price,
and from there it was only one small

00:18:18.240 --> 00:18:22.000
step to organizing the caravans
themselves.

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:26.880
By the end of the first millennium BC,
the Nabataeans had pushed out their

00:18:26.880 --> 00:18:32.799
rivals and now dominated the business of
transporting goods across the deserts of

00:18:32.799 --> 00:18:37.200
Arabia.
By the time the first books of the

00:18:37.200 --> 00:18:42.320
Hebrew Bible were being written down,
it's clear that the Arab kingdoms of the

00:18:42.320 --> 00:18:49.200
south were already making a killing.
In the Book of Kings, 10:15, the following

00:18:49.200 --> 00:18:54.400
account is made of the wealth of the
10th century King Solomon, with

00:18:54.400 --> 00:18:59.840
particular mention of the wealth of the
Arab kingdoms.

00:18:59.840 --> 00:19:04.400
Now, the weight of gold that came to
Solomon in one year

00:19:04.400 --> 00:19:11.840
was 603 score and six talents of gold.
Beside that, he had of the merchantmen

00:19:11.840 --> 00:19:17.360
and of the traffic of the spice
merchants and of all the kings of Arabia

00:19:17.360 --> 00:19:21.200
and of the governors of the country.

00:19:21.600 --> 00:19:27.840
The first truly solid account of the
Nabataeans comes secondhand from around

00:19:27.840 --> 00:19:31.280
the year
312 BC,

00:19:31.280 --> 00:19:38.039
and the Greek writer known as Hieronymus
of Cardia.

00:19:39.919 --> 00:19:45.360
Hieronymus wrote an apparently detailed
description of the Nabataean people,

00:19:45.360 --> 00:19:50.080
expounding on their history, their
culture, and their way of life. But

00:19:50.080 --> 00:19:55.520
unfortunately for us, that text hasn't
survived into the modern day,

00:19:55.520 --> 00:20:00.960
but he was used as a major source for
other later scholars like the Greek

00:20:00.960 --> 00:20:08.080
historian Diodorus of Sicily, writing
more than 300 years later.

00:20:08.080 --> 00:20:13.600
In his work, Diodorus gives a lengthy
description of the Nabataeans based on

00:20:13.600 --> 00:20:17.360
the earlier observations of Hieronymus
of Cardia.

00:20:17.360 --> 00:20:23.520
He paints a picture of an uncompromising
nomadic people who refused the comforts

00:20:23.520 --> 00:20:29.600
of settled society out of a desire for
independence.

00:20:29.840 --> 00:20:34.559
For the sake of those who do not know, it
will be useful to state in some detail

00:20:34.559 --> 00:20:39.039
the customs of these Arabs, by following
which, it is believed they preserve their

00:20:39.039 --> 00:20:42.799
liberty.
They range over a country that is partly

00:20:42.799 --> 00:20:47.520
desert and partly waterless, though a
small section of it is fruitful.

00:20:47.520 --> 00:20:51.919
They live in the open air, claiming as
native land a wilderness that has

00:20:51.919 --> 00:20:57.360
neither rivers nor abundant springs from
which it is possible for a hostile army

00:20:57.360 --> 00:21:02.480
to obtain water. It is their custom
neither to plant grain, set out any

00:21:02.480 --> 00:21:08.240
fruit-bearing tree, use wine, nor
construct any house, and if anyone is

00:21:08.240 --> 00:21:12.240
found acting contrary to this, death is
his penalty.

00:21:12.240 --> 00:21:16.159
They follow this custom because they
believe that those who possess these

00:21:16.159 --> 00:21:21.919
things are, in order to retain the use of
them, easily compelled by the powerful to

00:21:21.919 --> 00:21:24.799
do their bidding.

00:21:26.320 --> 00:21:32.320
Diodorus also recounts the great wealth
that the Nabataeans had amassed due to

00:21:32.320 --> 00:21:39.120
their control of crucial trade routes
for spices and incense.

00:21:39.360 --> 00:21:44.400
Some of them raised their camels, others
sheep, pasturing them in the desert.

00:21:44.400 --> 00:21:49.360
While there are many Arab tribes who use
the desert as pasture, the Nabataeans far

00:21:49.360 --> 00:21:53.840
surpass the others in wealth, although
they are not much more than ten thousand

00:21:53.840 --> 00:21:58.080
in number, for not a few of them are
accustomed to bring down to the sea

00:21:58.080 --> 00:22:02.559
frankincense and myrrh and the most
valuable kinds of spices which they

00:22:02.559 --> 00:22:06.320
procure from those who convey them.

00:22:07.600 --> 00:22:14.320
Frankincense and myrrh are the resins of
two different plants in the Burseraceae

00:22:14.320 --> 00:22:18.559
family,
gnarled and stunted trees that grow on

00:22:18.559 --> 00:22:23.440
the Arabian Peninsula in India and North
Africa.

00:22:23.440 --> 00:22:28.880
When the bark of these trees is damaged,
they have evolved to release resin from

00:22:28.880 --> 00:22:34.720
their wounds which forms a glassy seal,
protecting the plant's delicate insides

00:22:34.720 --> 00:22:39.200
from further harm.
But trees are also susceptible to

00:22:39.200 --> 00:22:45.440
bacterial infections just like we are,
and as an extra line of defense, these

00:22:45.440 --> 00:22:51.600
resins are filled with volatile
compounds that kill bacteria and fungi,

00:22:51.600 --> 00:22:58.080
similar to our own immune system. It's
these volatile chemicals that also act

00:22:58.080 --> 00:23:02.480
in interesting ways on the human sense
of smell.

00:23:02.480 --> 00:23:07.360
For at least the last five thousand
years, these resins have been used for

00:23:07.360 --> 00:23:12.960
their antibacterial properties in
medicine and for their striking aromas

00:23:12.960 --> 00:23:15.840
when burned.

00:23:16.080 --> 00:23:22.960
Frankincense releases a sweet and woody
scent with notes of lemon, while myrrh

00:23:22.960 --> 00:23:29.280
releases a smell that is more like spice,
bitterer with floral overtones.

00:23:29.280 --> 00:23:33.840
At harvest times,
farmers slice gashes into the barks of

00:23:33.840 --> 00:23:39.360
the trees and collect the milky resins
that ooze from within.

00:23:39.360 --> 00:23:46.880
Once exposed to air and sun, myrrh dries
and hardens to reddish-brown pea-sized

00:23:46.880 --> 00:23:53.440
chunks, while frankincense dries to pale
yellow, tear-shaped droplets.

00:23:53.440 --> 00:23:58.720
Diodorus of Sicily even claims that the
smells were so strong

00:23:58.720 --> 00:24:04.240
that sailors traveling up the coast of
Arabia could smell them as they sailed

00:24:04.240 --> 00:24:06.640
past.

00:24:08.159 --> 00:24:13.760
A group of Greek sailors who ran out of
supplies on the Arabian coast around the

00:24:13.760 --> 00:24:18.720
year 300 AD
landed on the shore in search of water,

00:24:18.720 --> 00:24:22.799
and stumbled upon a plantation of these
trees.

00:24:22.799 --> 00:24:28.000
They were later interviewed by the
botanist Theophrastes, who wrote down

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:34.320
everything they told him about the
methods of extracting these resins.

00:24:34.880 --> 00:24:38.320
They said that on the coasting voyage,
they landed to look for water on the

00:24:38.320 --> 00:24:43.279
mountains and saw these trees and the
manner of collecting their gums.

00:24:43.279 --> 00:24:46.960
They reported that with both trees,
incisions had been made,

00:24:46.960 --> 00:24:51.600
both in the stems and in the branches,
also that in some cases the gum was

00:24:51.600 --> 00:24:56.240
dropping, but that in others it remained
sticky to the tree, and that in some

00:24:56.240 --> 00:25:00.480
places, mats woven of palm leaves were
put underneath,

00:25:00.480 --> 00:25:07.039
while that which remained sticky to the
trees they scraped off with iron tools.

00:25:08.240 --> 00:25:13.840
The cultivation of these trees was
veiled in secrecy, and this secrecy gave

00:25:13.840 --> 00:25:20.080
rise to outlandish myths.
The historian Herodotus, writing in the

00:25:20.080 --> 00:25:24.559
5th century BC,
recorded the process for harvesting

00:25:24.559 --> 00:25:28.880
these incenses,
along with an account of a supposed race

00:25:28.880 --> 00:25:35.760
of monsters that guarded them.
Arabia is the furthest of the inhabited

00:25:35.760 --> 00:25:42.000
lands in the direction of the midday,
and in it alone of all lands grow

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:47.200
frankincense and myrrh.
These are got with difficulty by the

00:25:47.200 --> 00:25:51.039
Arabians,
for these trees which produce

00:25:51.039 --> 00:25:55.440
frankincense are guarded by winged
serpents,

00:25:55.440 --> 00:26:01.520
small in size and of various colors,
which watch in great numbers about each

00:26:01.520 --> 00:26:04.400
tree,
and they cannot be driven away from the

00:26:04.400 --> 00:26:11.840
trees by any other thing but only the
smoke of the storax.

00:26:12.080 --> 00:26:17.200
We will never know whether this was a
simple legend or whether it was a

00:26:17.200 --> 00:26:23.520
purposeful piece of disinformation
spread by Arab frankincense farmers to

00:26:23.520 --> 00:26:27.279
scare others away from their lucrative
industry.

00:26:27.279 --> 00:26:31.520
If this latter was the case, then it
seems to have worked;

00:26:31.520 --> 00:26:36.799
the stories of venomous flying snakes
were repeated by a number of other

00:26:36.799 --> 00:26:40.960
ancient Greek writers,
and few of those who explored the coast

00:26:40.960 --> 00:26:46.720
of Arabia by sea were ever brave enough
to venture inland to see the incense

00:26:46.720 --> 00:26:50.400
plantations for themselves.

00:26:50.640 --> 00:26:55.039
It's not hard to see
why these commodities were so sought

00:26:55.039 --> 00:26:59.120
after.
Towns and cities of the bronze and iron

00:26:59.120 --> 00:27:04.960
age would likely have been a potent mix
of pungent smells.

00:27:04.960 --> 00:27:10.480
Even in the most refined cities,
sanitation was in its early stages, if it

00:27:10.480 --> 00:27:14.480
existed at all,
and little centralized planning would

00:27:14.480 --> 00:27:19.440
often mean that waste would build up
close to where people lived and worked.

00:27:19.440 --> 00:27:24.880
With no refrigeration, food would spoil
quickly, and industries like leather

00:27:24.880 --> 00:27:30.720
tanning used dung and urine to produce
their products. All of this would have

00:27:30.720 --> 00:27:36.320
combined to create a heady assault on
the noses of all the people who lived

00:27:36.320 --> 00:27:40.080
there.
For the rich, alleviating this

00:27:40.080 --> 00:27:45.360
discomfort was something they were
willing to pay for.

00:27:46.559 --> 00:27:52.640
Aside from this obvious use, the burning
of incense also took on a significant

00:27:52.640 --> 00:27:58.960
spiritual dimension.
Temples and places of religious worship

00:27:58.960 --> 00:28:05.279
wanted to create a clear divide between
the inside of the temple, a holy, sacred

00:28:05.279 --> 00:28:12.559
space, and the dirty, smelly world outside,
and incense was one of the best ways to

00:28:12.559 --> 00:28:17.039
do this.
Since ancient times, people had noticed

00:28:17.039 --> 00:28:22.240
the connection between bad smells and
illness and death.

00:28:22.240 --> 00:28:28.240
Our sense of smell evolved in part to
protect us from harmful bacteria in

00:28:28.240 --> 00:28:33.679
waste and decaying matter,
and so naturally, people noticed that

00:28:33.679 --> 00:28:39.679
those who lived close to foul-smelling
places like sewers and waste heaps would

00:28:39.679 --> 00:28:45.760
get sick more often and even
die. Since the earliest texts have been

00:28:45.760 --> 00:28:50.720
recorded, it's clear that people
considered the presence of bad smells to

00:28:50.720 --> 00:28:56.480
be evidence of the existence of evil
spirits, invisible to the eye but

00:28:56.480 --> 00:29:02.000
lingering in the air, waiting to cause
disease and misery to the people around

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:05.679
them.
A large part of the responsibility of a

00:29:05.679 --> 00:29:10.840
temple was to give people comfort from
the daily horrors of disease and

00:29:10.840 --> 00:29:15.600
misfortune, and to do this, they would
need to create a space where these

00:29:15.600 --> 00:29:22.960
putrid smells and the evil associated
with them were not allowed entry.

00:29:22.960 --> 00:29:29.520
This use of incense to create a sense of
holy space is truly ancient.

00:29:29.520 --> 00:29:35.360
It was mentioned as part of rituals in
Homer's Odyssey, and the Book of Exodus

00:29:35.360 --> 00:29:40.799
even describes a particular blend of
frankincense and other spices to be

00:29:40.799 --> 00:29:46.159
ground and burnt in the sacred altar
before the ark of the covenant, and even

00:29:46.159 --> 00:29:52.159
goes so far as to forbid its use for any
other purpose.

00:29:52.320 --> 00:29:58.720
Then the Lord said to Moses,
take fragrant spices, gum resin, onycha, and

00:29:58.720 --> 00:30:03.120
galbanum,
and pure frankincense all in equal

00:30:03.120 --> 00:30:09.919
amounts, and make a fragrant blend of
incense, the work of a perfumer.

00:30:09.919 --> 00:30:14.799
It is to be salted and pure
and sacred.

00:30:14.799 --> 00:30:19.679
Grind some of it to a powder and place
it in front of the ark of the covenant

00:30:19.679 --> 00:30:25.600
law in the tent of meeting.
It shall be most holy to you.

00:30:25.600 --> 00:30:30.240
Do not make any incense with this
formula for yourselves.

00:30:30.240 --> 00:30:36.320
Whoever makes incense like it to enjoy
its fragrance must be cut off from their

00:30:36.320 --> 00:30:38.720
people.

00:30:40.720 --> 00:30:45.840
From this connection to the divine,
incense would soon become integral to

00:30:45.840 --> 00:30:50.880
the function of royalty.
Myrrh was used in the anointing rituals

00:30:50.880 --> 00:30:56.320
of Hebrew queens and in the embalming
process for the mummies of Egyptian

00:30:56.320 --> 00:31:00.640
pharaohs.
In the Christian New Testament, the

00:31:00.640 --> 00:31:05.919
Gospel of Matthew describes a group of
wise men who travel from the east to

00:31:05.919 --> 00:31:11.440
attend the birth of Jesus, and who bring
him the traditional offerings given to

00:31:11.440 --> 00:31:15.679
royalty;
gold, frankincense, and myrrh,

00:31:15.679 --> 00:31:22.159
gifts designed to reinforce his claim to
being born as King of the Jews and the

00:31:22.159 --> 00:31:28.480
descendant of King David.
In other words, incense around this time

00:31:28.480 --> 00:31:33.679
was serious business.
These fragrances were not simply

00:31:33.679 --> 00:31:38.320
frivolous luxuries, but they were
essential tools in the way that

00:31:38.320 --> 00:31:43.360
religious authority and the power of the
state were constructed.

00:31:43.360 --> 00:31:48.960
As societies became more centralized and
these institutions grew in power and

00:31:48.960 --> 00:31:53.919
wealth, the demand for incense would only
increase.

00:31:53.919 --> 00:32:00.080
As the second and first centuries BC
passed by, the Nabataean people found

00:32:00.080 --> 00:32:05.360
themselves at the very heart of this
crucial industry.

00:32:05.360 --> 00:32:10.399
Camels would soon lumber across the
Nabataean roads with boxes of

00:32:10.399 --> 00:32:17.279
frankincense and myrrh from Oman, sacks
of spices from India, and bolts of cloth

00:32:17.279 --> 00:32:22.880
from Syria,
as well as sugar and ivory from Africa.

00:32:22.880 --> 00:32:28.159
All of this would pass through a
city that sat at the crossroads of

00:32:28.159 --> 00:32:32.559
multiple trade routes,
a place that would come to hold a

00:32:32.559 --> 00:32:36.960
semi-mythical reputation around the
known world.

00:32:36.960 --> 00:32:41.279
To the Nabataeans, this city was known as
Raqm,

00:32:41.279 --> 00:32:46.399
but to the people of the wider world, it
would come to be known by the Greek word

00:32:46.399 --> 00:32:50.960
for rock, the element from which it was
carved.

00:32:50.960 --> 00:32:55.880
This was the city of Petra.

00:33:04.960 --> 00:33:10.480
The site of Petra has been inhabited for
at least the last 7,000 years,

00:33:10.480 --> 00:33:15.039
and this is partly due to its
interesting geology.

00:33:15.039 --> 00:33:21.519
A freshwater spring rises from the
ground here, known as Musa’s Spring, and

00:33:21.519 --> 00:33:26.159
it's held in traditional beliefs to be
the place where the biblical figure

00:33:26.159 --> 00:33:32.640
Moses once struck a rock with his staff
and caused water to gush from the desert

00:33:32.640 --> 00:33:36.880
stones.
The appearance of a spring of water

00:33:36.880 --> 00:33:40.880
in this arid desert
really must have seemed miraculous to

00:33:40.880 --> 00:33:47.039
the early peoples who settled here.
As rainwaters permeate through these

00:33:47.039 --> 00:33:53.279
porous sandstones, they gather in
subterranean pools, and these waters

00:33:53.279 --> 00:33:58.320
slowly leech out of the rocks along the
paths of least resistance.

00:33:58.320 --> 00:34:03.919
This means that the very stones of
Petra's landscape act like enormous

00:34:03.919 --> 00:34:08.000
water towers,
slowly releasing their stores of water

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:12.079
through the long, dry months of the
Arabian summer.

00:34:12.079 --> 00:34:17.040
Over millions of years,
these spring waters, along with the brief

00:34:17.040 --> 00:34:22.960
but heavy winter rains, have cut through
the sandstone bluffs so that a narrow

00:34:22.960 --> 00:34:28.800
ravine known as a Siq wound its way
through the solid stone.

00:34:28.800 --> 00:34:32.720
Beyond this was a perfectly enclosed
area

00:34:32.720 --> 00:34:37.440
sheltered by high cliffs from the desert
wind and sands,

00:34:37.440 --> 00:34:42.480
and with a constant supply of fresh
water.

00:34:42.480 --> 00:34:47.919
The first century Roman author and
naturalist, Pliny the Elder, gives one

00:34:47.919 --> 00:34:53.440
early account of the city in his work,
Natural History.

00:34:53.440 --> 00:35:00.880
The Nabataeans inhabit a town named Petra.
It lies in a deep valley in little less

00:35:00.880 --> 00:35:07.200
than two miles wide, and is surrounded by
inaccessible mountains with a river

00:35:07.200 --> 00:35:12.160
flowing between them.
At Petra, two roads meet.

00:35:12.160 --> 00:35:18.800
Its distance from the town of Gaza on
the Mediterranean coast is 600 miles, and

00:35:18.800 --> 00:35:24.720
from the Persian Gulf is
635 miles.

00:35:25.359 --> 00:35:31.119
This naturally-occurring spring water
was enough to support a small population,

00:35:31.119 --> 00:35:37.040
but as the city's importance grew and
the trade caravans got larger, the strain

00:35:37.040 --> 00:35:43.200
on its supply must have grown and grown.
To enhance the natural water systems of

00:35:43.200 --> 00:35:49.200
the region, the Nabataeans began to build
complex water control systems, cutting

00:35:49.200 --> 00:35:54.400
aqueducts into the sandstone of the
mountains, and even building underground

00:35:54.400 --> 00:36:00.480
plumbing systems out of terracotta pipes
to divert the water of several nearby

00:36:00.480 --> 00:36:04.800
springs directly into the heart of the
settlement.

00:36:04.800 --> 00:36:09.599
They also learned techniques for
gathering rainfall that they used to

00:36:09.599 --> 00:36:14.400
enormous effect.
Although the climate of the region

00:36:14.400 --> 00:36:20.320
wasn't quite as arid 2,000 years ago as
it is today, this landscape was still a

00:36:20.320 --> 00:36:24.240
desert.
Rain in these parts came extremely

00:36:24.240 --> 00:36:28.320
rarely,
and the so-called rainy season, around

00:36:28.320 --> 00:36:34.079
January, could consist of just one or two
spells of rain in a year. In the height

00:36:34.079 --> 00:36:40.720
of summer, rainfall stops entirely.
So, the Nabataeans worked tirelessly

00:36:40.720 --> 00:36:45.599
to maximize the amount of water they
could gather during these few rainy

00:36:45.599 --> 00:36:49.359
spells.
Rainwater would naturally gather in

00:36:49.359 --> 00:36:54.320
depressions and hollows, and for
centuries, herdsmen had taken advantage

00:36:54.320 --> 00:36:59.599
of these natural pools.
But sandstone is a porous rock, and the

00:36:59.599 --> 00:37:03.520
water would naturally drain away over
time.

00:37:03.520 --> 00:37:08.720
To fix this problem, the Nabataeans
worked to line these natural pools with

00:37:08.720 --> 00:37:13.440
hard stucco plaster,
meaning that the water would remain and

00:37:13.440 --> 00:37:17.359
could be used long into the season of
drought.

00:37:17.359 --> 00:37:23.440
They built large dams across the valleys
to gather rainwater into reservoirs and

00:37:23.440 --> 00:37:28.160
also reduce the flooding that occurred
each year as rainwater followed the

00:37:28.160 --> 00:37:33.200
well-worn channels it had cut for
millions of years through the red rock

00:37:33.200 --> 00:37:38.720
of the valley.
The Nabataeans’ expert control of scarce

00:37:38.720 --> 00:37:43.839
water resources meant that Petra was
able to grow to eventually house as many

00:37:43.839 --> 00:37:49.680
as 20,000 permanent residents
and to support the constant arrival of

00:37:49.680 --> 00:37:55.680
large trading caravans, many of them made
up of hundreds of people and camels,

00:37:55.680 --> 00:37:59.839
arriving thirsty from the long desert
roads.

00:37:59.839 --> 00:38:04.640
Soon, the water was even abundant
enough that it could be used for more

00:38:04.640 --> 00:38:10.240
luxurious purposes.
The citizens of Petra would soon be able

00:38:10.240 --> 00:38:16.240
to bathe, make wine, cultivate fruit, and
stroll through their streets in the

00:38:16.240 --> 00:38:21.599
shade of palm trees.
Archaeology shows that Petra was not

00:38:21.599 --> 00:38:26.240
just a city of tombs;
in its time of flourishing, it was

00:38:26.240 --> 00:38:32.800
sprawling with lush gardens and pleasant
fountains, enormous temples, and luxurious

00:38:32.800 --> 00:38:36.960
villas.
The Roman writer Strabo gives some

00:38:36.960 --> 00:38:41.520
glimpse of this.
The metropolis of the Nabataeans is

00:38:41.520 --> 00:38:47.040
Petra, as it is called, for it lies on a
site which is otherwise smooth and level,

00:38:47.040 --> 00:38:52.640
but it is fortified all around by a rock,
the outside parts of the site being

00:38:52.640 --> 00:38:58.560
precipitous and sheer, and the inside
parts having springs in abundance, both

00:38:58.560 --> 00:39:02.320
for domestic purposes and for watering
gardens.

00:39:02.320 --> 00:39:07.200
Outside the circuit of the rock, most of
the territory is desert, in particular

00:39:07.200 --> 00:39:10.320
towards Judaea.

00:39:10.480 --> 00:39:15.760
Some of the Nabataeans’ own
inscriptions clearly reference gardens

00:39:15.760 --> 00:39:21.040
existing within the city.
The following inscription from a tomb at

00:39:21.040 --> 00:39:26.079
Petra illustrates some of the
flourishing plant life that once stood

00:39:26.079 --> 00:39:29.680
here and which may have belonged to a
temple,

00:39:29.680 --> 00:39:36.240
and its description stands in stark
contrast to the barren sand and stones

00:39:36.240 --> 00:39:40.400
that today stretch out around it.

00:39:40.800 --> 00:39:45.920
This tomb and the large burial chamber
within it and the small burial chamber

00:39:45.920 --> 00:39:51.599
beyond it, the enclosure in front of them,
and the porticos and the rooms within it,

00:39:51.599 --> 00:39:56.480
and the gardens and pleasure garden, and
the walls of water, and the cistern and

00:39:56.480 --> 00:40:01.760
walls, and all the rest of the property
which in these places are sacred and

00:40:01.760 --> 00:40:05.520
dedicated to Dushara, the god of our
lord,

00:40:05.520 --> 00:40:12.079
and his sacred throne and all the
gods. Outside the city, in the surrounding

00:40:12.079 --> 00:40:16.640
countryside,
water control was even more crucial. Even

00:40:16.640 --> 00:40:22.160
with enough water, the Nabataeans still
needed to eat, and to do so, they would

00:40:22.160 --> 00:40:27.440
employ a unique style of farming that
maximized the potential of the difficult

00:40:27.440 --> 00:40:31.440
terrain.
They would contour a large area of the

00:40:31.440 --> 00:40:37.359
land, digging it out into a shallow
funnel sloping down to a single point,

00:40:37.359 --> 00:40:41.040
and at this point, they would plant a
single fruit tree.

00:40:41.040 --> 00:40:46.079
When the rains came, the water would
drain down to this central point and the

00:40:46.079 --> 00:40:51.200
tree could survive. To plant an orchard
of trees using this method, you need

00:40:51.200 --> 00:40:57.200
about fifty times the normal space, but it
was an effective technique, and out here

00:40:57.200 --> 00:41:04.000
in the desert, one thing the Nabataeans
had no shortage of was space.

00:41:04.079 --> 00:41:10.160
The Nabataeans also used their expertise
at water control to enormous strategic

00:41:10.160 --> 00:41:14.000
advantage.
Diodorus of Sicily recounts how they

00:41:14.000 --> 00:41:19.200
built a system of secret hidden
reservoirs across the desert, meaning

00:41:19.200 --> 00:41:24.240
that only they could take advantage of
them, ensuring that no competitors could

00:41:24.240 --> 00:41:29.760
move in on their lucrative trade routes.
In times of war, their secret

00:41:29.760 --> 00:41:34.560
reservoirs also gave them an advantage
against their enemies,

00:41:34.560 --> 00:41:38.319
as Diodorus recalls.

00:41:38.640 --> 00:41:43.920
They are exceptionally fond of freedom,
and whenever a strong force of enemies

00:41:43.920 --> 00:41:49.200
comes near, they take refuge in the
desert, using this as a fortress, for it

00:41:49.200 --> 00:41:54.400
lacks water and cannot be crossed by
others, but to them alone.

00:41:54.400 --> 00:41:59.040
Since they have prepared subterranean
reservoirs lined with stucco, the mouths

00:41:59.040 --> 00:42:03.520
of which they make very small. After
filling these reservoirs with rainwater,

00:42:03.520 --> 00:42:07.839
they close the openings, making them even
with the rest of the ground, and they

00:42:07.839 --> 00:42:12.960
leave signs that are known to themselves
but are unrecognizable by others. They

00:42:12.960 --> 00:42:17.119
water their cattle every other day so
that if they flee through waterless

00:42:17.119 --> 00:42:22.720
places, they may not need a continuous
supply of water.

00:42:24.400 --> 00:42:30.240
But despite the immense difficulties of
maintaining this city, its position meant

00:42:30.240 --> 00:42:35.760
it was all worth it.
That's because Petra sat at the center

00:42:35.760 --> 00:42:42.560
of a spider's web of trade routes
spreading off in every direction.

00:42:42.560 --> 00:42:48.079
To the east, desert roads led to the port
towns of Basrah and Dahran

00:42:48.079 --> 00:42:54.960
in the Persian Gulf, where spices from
East Asia like cinnamon, ginger, nutmeg,

00:42:54.960 --> 00:43:00.880
and pepper flowed, as well as precious
stones from India and fine silks from

00:43:00.880 --> 00:43:06.000
China.
From the south, frankincense and myrrh

00:43:06.000 --> 00:43:11.680
poured into Petra from the incense
fields of Yemen and Oman.

00:43:11.680 --> 00:43:17.760
Petra connected the nearby Red Sea port
of Aqaba with the Mediterranean port

00:43:17.760 --> 00:43:24.240
town of Gaza, connecting the markets of
Eastern Africa with those of Europe,

00:43:24.240 --> 00:43:30.079
and on the roads to the north lay the
great cities of Damascus and Antioch.

00:43:30.079 --> 00:43:35.359
To the west, the roads led from Petra
into Egypt, where tin was in constant

00:43:35.359 --> 00:43:40.800
demand, brought from Afghanistan, along
with the brilliant blue stone lapis

00:43:40.800 --> 00:43:45.280
lazuli.
The black volcanic glass obsidian was

00:43:45.280 --> 00:43:50.400
brought from Abyssinia.
Perfumes and scented oils, as well as

00:43:50.400 --> 00:43:56.319
cosmetic powders and eye shadows, flowed
north to Greece, stored in containers

00:43:56.319 --> 00:44:01.280
carved from giant clam shells harvested
in the Red Sea.

00:44:01.280 --> 00:44:07.040
The tarry substance bitumen was farmed
from the Dead Sea and brought south to

00:44:07.040 --> 00:44:13.119
Egypt to help in the embalming process
for mummies and to waterproof the hulls

00:44:13.119 --> 00:44:17.359
of ships.
The Nabataeans were so crucial to the

00:44:17.359 --> 00:44:22.720
transferring of all of these goods by
land and sea that they were able to

00:44:22.720 --> 00:44:27.520
charge a tax
equal to a full quarter of all the goods

00:44:27.520 --> 00:44:32.880
that passed through their lands.
As a result, the Nabataeans would soon

00:44:32.880 --> 00:44:40.640
grow fabulously, even absurdly, wealthy.
But soon, others would start to look with

00:44:40.640 --> 00:44:46.680
jealous eyes to the fortune they had
made.

00:44:53.359 --> 00:44:59.040
The Nabataeans were not a warrior people,
and it seems that they preferred,

00:44:59.040 --> 00:45:04.319
wherever possible, not to fight.
But they were more than capable of

00:45:04.319 --> 00:45:10.240
defending themselves when attacked, as
one colorful episode from their history

00:45:10.240 --> 00:45:12.720
shows.

00:45:15.839 --> 00:45:22.400
The society of the Nabataeans rose into
a world that still bore the marks of one

00:45:22.400 --> 00:45:27.760
of history's most dramatic reshufflings
of power.

00:45:27.760 --> 00:45:34.480
Towards the end of the 4th century BC,
the 20-year-old King Alexander of the

00:45:34.480 --> 00:45:39.280
mountainous kingdom of Macedon in
northern Greece had embarked on a

00:45:39.280 --> 00:45:44.839
ten-year campaign that would see him
topple the Persian Empire and sweep

00:45:44.839 --> 00:45:51.280
eastwards to capture vast swathes of
territory throughout Central Asia, even

00:45:51.280 --> 00:45:58.640
invading India.
Alexander died in the year 323 BC, in the

00:45:58.640 --> 00:46:04.720
city of Babylon,
and his empire immediately disintegrated.

00:46:04.720 --> 00:46:11.119
He left in his wake a series of large
Greek kingdoms stretching from Pakistan

00:46:11.119 --> 00:46:14.800
to Egypt,
and each of these began fighting with

00:46:14.800 --> 00:46:20.319
one another over who would rule the
remnants of the empire.

00:46:20.319 --> 00:46:25.599
One of these kingdoms was ruled by a
King Antigonus who had been a general

00:46:25.599 --> 00:46:31.440
under Alexander and who had served him
as governor of much of the Middle East.

00:46:31.440 --> 00:46:37.200
Antigonus had lost an eye after
apparently being struck by shrapnel from

00:46:37.200 --> 00:46:42.720
a splintering catapult bolt while
serving under Alexander's father, and so,

00:46:42.720 --> 00:46:49.599
he has gone down in history by the name
Antigonus Monophthalmus, or Antigonus

00:46:49.599 --> 00:46:55.359
the One-Eyed.
Antigonus was also mono-maniacal.

00:46:55.359 --> 00:47:00.640
He soon embarked on a determined
campaign to reunite Alexander's great

00:47:00.640 --> 00:47:06.960
empire and rule over it himself. He
quickly swept through Syria, taking the

00:47:06.960 --> 00:47:12.079
lands of his rivals, and conquered down
the Mediterranean coast,

00:47:12.079 --> 00:47:17.760
eventually reaching the borders of the
wealthy lands of the Nabataeans.

00:47:17.760 --> 00:47:24.079
War is an expensive business, and as with
most warmongers, Antigonus was

00:47:24.079 --> 00:47:29.680
permanently short of money.
Soon, he began to look hungrily to the

00:47:29.680 --> 00:47:36.640
south, and dreamed of seizing the fabled
wealth of Petra for himself.

00:47:36.640 --> 00:47:44.640
In the year 312 BC, he ordered one of his
generals, a man named Athenaeus, to march

00:47:44.640 --> 00:47:49.839
into the desert and seize as much as he
could of the wealth of these Nabataean

00:47:49.839 --> 00:47:54.160
traders.
The disciplined and battle-hardened

00:47:54.160 --> 00:47:59.599
phalanxes of Antigonus were among the
best soldiers in the world,

00:47:59.599 --> 00:48:05.040
some having served under Alexander
himself, and these crack troops don't

00:48:05.040 --> 00:48:08.800
seem to have expected much of a
challenge.

00:48:08.800 --> 00:48:15.040
Athenaeus marched out into the desert
from Judaea with an army made up of 4,000

00:48:15.040 --> 00:48:21.119
foot soldiers armed with long pikes, and
600 horsemen,

00:48:21.119 --> 00:48:25.839
as Diodorus of Sicily recounts.

00:48:26.400 --> 00:48:31.599
Deciding that this people was hostile to
his interests, he selected one of his

00:48:31.599 --> 00:48:38.720
friends, Athenaeus, and gave him 4,000
light-foot soldiers and 600 horsemen

00:48:38.720 --> 00:48:45.119
fitted for speed, and ordered him to set
upon the barbarians suddenly and cut off

00:48:45.119 --> 00:48:49.559
all their cattle as plunder.

00:48:50.319 --> 00:48:57.040
It took Athenaeus and his soldiers three
days to travel the 160 kilometers across

00:48:57.040 --> 00:49:00.640
the desert,
but soon they came into view of the

00:49:00.640 --> 00:49:06.640
legendary stone city.
Athenaeus ordered his men to prepare for

00:49:06.640 --> 00:49:12.079
a nighttime attack.
We can imagine the sight of the Greek

00:49:12.079 --> 00:49:17.680
army waiting and watching,
as the shadows stretched long over the

00:49:17.680 --> 00:49:24.079
rosy stones of the city and the sun sat
in a purply haze over the Jordanian

00:49:24.079 --> 00:49:27.599
desert.
When night fell,

00:49:27.599 --> 00:49:33.359
the soldiers stormed into the city.
They found it almost completely

00:49:33.359 --> 00:49:37.359
undefended.
There seems to have been no permanent

00:49:37.359 --> 00:49:44.319
garrison guarding the city of Petra, and
the Nabataean men were away on business.

00:49:44.319 --> 00:49:49.920
What followed was a frenzy of looting,
and here we can get a sense for the vast

00:49:49.920 --> 00:49:54.079
wealth that had been amassed in this
city.

00:49:54.079 --> 00:49:59.119
Athenaeus and his men loaded themselves
with as much frankincense and myrrh as

00:49:59.119 --> 00:50:05.839
their animals could carry, and reportedly
made away with nearly 14 tons of silver.

00:50:05.839 --> 00:50:10.800
Not content with that, they also rounded
up all of the women and children they

00:50:10.800 --> 00:50:16.240
could and abducted them with the
intention of selling them as slaves, as

00:50:16.240 --> 00:50:20.960
Diodorus recalls.
Of those that were caught there,

00:50:20.960 --> 00:50:26.319
some he slew at once, some he took as
prisoners, and others who were wounded he

00:50:26.319 --> 00:50:29.440
left behind,
and of the frankincense and myrrh, he

00:50:29.440 --> 00:50:35.680
gathered together the larger part and
about 500 talents of silver.

00:50:35.680 --> 00:50:41.119
The Greeks, hardly believing how easy it
had been, marched off with their slaves

00:50:41.119 --> 00:50:47.040
and loot as fast as they could, and made
their way back along the road to safety.

00:50:47.040 --> 00:50:52.000
Weighed down with treasure and prisoners,
and with their horses no doubt

00:50:52.000 --> 00:50:57.280
struggling in the desert landscape,
they traveled about 36 kilometers from

00:50:57.280 --> 00:51:01.599
Petra and thought that there would be
safe to make camp.

00:51:01.599 --> 00:51:07.280
But they had not reckoned on the
camel-powered armies of the Nabataeans.

00:51:07.280 --> 00:51:12.880
Only a few hours after Athenaeus and his
soldiers had left Petra, the first

00:51:12.880 --> 00:51:16.960
Nabataean men began to return to the
city.

00:51:16.960 --> 00:51:22.640
Finding its houses and temples looted
and their wives and children gone, they

00:51:22.640 --> 00:51:27.760
heard about the Greek attack from
wounded survivors and began an immediate

00:51:27.760 --> 00:51:32.240
pursuit.
They sent out riders and gathered more

00:51:32.240 --> 00:51:37.280
men from every village they passed
through until the Nabataean force had

00:51:37.280 --> 00:51:41.920
swollen to a horde of 8,000
camel riders.

00:51:41.920 --> 00:51:45.839
They loped across the desert with
exceptional speed,

00:51:45.839 --> 00:51:53.680
easily outpacing the Greek horses, and
caught up to Athenaeus’ camp by nightfall.

00:51:53.680 --> 00:51:58.480
While the men of Athenaeus’ were encamped
with little thought of the enemy, and

00:51:58.480 --> 00:52:02.480
because of their weariness, were in deep
sleep.

00:52:02.480 --> 00:52:07.520
Some of their prisoners escaped secretly,
and the Nabataeans, learning from them

00:52:07.520 --> 00:52:12.400
the condition of the enemy, attacked the
camp at about the third watch, being no

00:52:12.400 --> 00:52:17.640
less than 8,000 in number.

00:52:18.000 --> 00:52:24.000
Under cover of darkness, the enraged
Nabataeans swept into the Greek camp and

00:52:24.000 --> 00:52:28.160
slaughtered everyone they could find.

00:52:28.400 --> 00:52:32.400
Most of the hostile troops they
slaughtered where they lay;

00:52:32.400 --> 00:52:37.680
the rest they slew with their javelins
as they awoke and sprang to arms.

00:52:37.680 --> 00:52:41.200
In the end,
all the foot soldiers were slain,

00:52:41.200 --> 00:52:46.720
but of the horsemen, about fifty escaped, and
of these the larger part were wounded.

00:52:46.720 --> 00:52:50.800
When the Nabataeans had manfully
punished the enemy, they themselves

00:52:50.800 --> 00:52:56.160
returned to the rock with the property
that they had recovered.

00:52:56.319 --> 00:53:02.319
Every single Greek foot soldier was
killed, and only about fifty of the Greek

00:53:02.319 --> 00:53:08.640
cavalry were able to flee the scene and
trickle back across the desert.

00:53:08.640 --> 00:53:12.800
For the Greeks, this was an incredible
humiliation,

00:53:12.800 --> 00:53:18.319
but it's clear the Nabataeans had no
interest in fighting a war. They sent a

00:53:18.319 --> 00:53:24.240
message to King Antigonus in Aramaic, the
common language of the ancient Middle

00:53:24.240 --> 00:53:30.000
East, explaining why they had wiped out
his army and asking for no further

00:53:30.000 --> 00:53:34.559
aggression against them.
The embarrassed Greek king clearly tried

00:53:34.559 --> 00:53:38.319
his best to save face.

00:53:38.559 --> 00:53:43.200
To Antigonus they wrote a letter in
Syrian characters in which they accused

00:53:43.200 --> 00:53:48.240
Athenaeus and vindicated themselves.
Antigonus replied to them, agreeing that

00:53:48.240 --> 00:53:52.559
they had been justified in defending
themselves, but he found fault with

00:53:52.559 --> 00:53:57.520
Athenaeus, saying that he made the attack
contrary to the instructions he had been

00:53:57.520 --> 00:53:59.920
given.
He did this,

00:53:59.920 --> 00:54:05.839
hiding his own intentions and desiring
to delude the barbarians into a sense of

00:54:05.839 --> 00:54:09.440
security.
The Arabs were highly pleased because

00:54:09.440 --> 00:54:14.000
they seemed to have been relieved of
great fears, yet they did not altogether

00:54:14.000 --> 00:54:18.720
trust the words of Antigonus.
Regarding their prospects as uncertain,

00:54:18.720 --> 00:54:23.359
they placed watchmen upon the hills from
which it was easy to see from a great

00:54:23.359 --> 00:54:27.760
distance the passes into Arabia.

00:54:28.640 --> 00:54:34.000
This final act of caution seems to have
been completely justified.

00:54:34.000 --> 00:54:40.319
In fact, King Antigonus had no intention
of maintaining the peace or accepting

00:54:40.319 --> 00:54:45.440
defeat at the hands of a people he
considered to be barbarians.

00:54:45.440 --> 00:54:51.040
He ordered his son Demetrius to march
back into the Nabataean lands and

00:54:51.040 --> 00:54:56.480
accomplish what Athenaeus could not,
this time with another 4,000 foot

00:54:56.480 --> 00:55:01.680
soldiers and a much larger force of
4,000 cavalry.

00:55:01.680 --> 00:55:07.640
But Demetrius would not have much more
success.

00:55:09.359 --> 00:55:13.599
The watchmen that the Nabataeans had
placed along their borders quickly

00:55:13.599 --> 00:55:20.160
spotted the advancing Greeks and lit
warning beacons on the hilltops.

00:55:20.160 --> 00:55:26.240
The desert people scattered their flocks,
hiding them away in narrow crevices and

00:55:26.240 --> 00:55:30.640
hidden places,
and took all of their precious goods,

00:55:30.640 --> 00:55:36.799
women, and children with them.
They all flared to a stony fortress,

00:55:36.799 --> 00:55:43.119
possibly a flat-topped mountain named Umm
Al-Biyara, the tallest point around the

00:55:43.119 --> 00:55:46.160
city of Petra.

00:55:46.640 --> 00:55:51.520
Demetrius, on arriving at the rock and
finding that the flocks had been removed,

00:55:51.520 --> 00:55:55.280
made repeated assaults upon the
stronghold.

00:55:55.280 --> 00:56:00.640
Those within resisted stoutly and easily
had the upper hand because of the height

00:56:00.640 --> 00:56:06.960
of the place. So, on this day, after he
had continued the struggle until evening,

00:56:06.960 --> 00:56:11.520
he recalled his soldiers by a trumpet
call.

00:56:12.799 --> 00:56:17.440
The Greek general Demetrius was clearly
frustrated.

00:56:17.440 --> 00:56:22.559
The single narrow approach up to the
mountain's stronghold made a direct

00:56:22.559 --> 00:56:27.599
attack on it virtually impossible, and
it's clear that at least someone among

00:56:27.599 --> 00:56:34.319
the Nabataeans had a gift with words.
As Demetrius approached the next day for

00:56:34.319 --> 00:56:40.160
a fresh round of assaults, someone called
down from the walls with the following

00:56:40.160 --> 00:56:46.480
impassioned plea,
which Diodorus of Sicily recounts.

00:56:48.720 --> 00:56:53.440
On the next day, however, when he had
advanced upon the rock, one of the

00:56:53.440 --> 00:56:59.760
barbarians called to him, saying, “King
Demetrius, with what desire or under what

00:56:59.760 --> 00:57:04.079
compulsion do you war against us who
live in the desert and in a land that

00:57:04.079 --> 00:57:10.240
has neither water, nor grain,
nor wine, nor any other thing whatever of

00:57:10.240 --> 00:57:14.240
those that pertain to the necessities of
life among you?

00:57:14.240 --> 00:57:19.599
For we, since we are in no way willing to
be slaves, have all taken refuge in a

00:57:19.599 --> 00:57:24.079
land that lacks all the things that are
valued among other peoples and have

00:57:24.079 --> 00:57:29.440
chosen to live a life in the desert,
harming you not at all.

00:57:29.440 --> 00:57:34.799
We therefore beg both you and your
father to do us no injury,

00:57:34.799 --> 00:57:40.480
but after receiving gifts from us to
withdraw your army and henceforth regard

00:57:40.480 --> 00:57:46.160
the Nabataeans as your friends,
for neither can you, if you wish remain

00:57:46.160 --> 00:57:52.079
here many days since you lack water and
all other necessary supplies, nor can you

00:57:52.079 --> 00:57:56.480
force us to live a different life.

00:57:57.680 --> 00:58:03.920
Here, we can see the Nabataeans deploying
both of their great strengths.

00:58:03.920 --> 00:58:09.839
Their strategic control of the water,
secreted away in hidden reservoirs, meant

00:58:09.839 --> 00:58:14.160
that any protracted siege of the city
was impossible,

00:58:14.160 --> 00:58:18.960
and their enormous wealth often meant
that they could simply pay off their

00:58:18.960 --> 00:58:23.680
enemies.
Demetrius must have sensed that the

00:58:23.680 --> 00:58:28.240
siege was hopeless.
He agreed to accept a payment from the

00:58:28.240 --> 00:58:34.640
Nabataeans and marched back to his lands
not exactly victorious, but at least a

00:58:34.640 --> 00:58:39.839
good deal richer.
His father, King Antigonus, seems to have

00:58:39.839 --> 00:58:46.960
been quite angry at his son's decision,
as Diodorus relates.

00:58:46.960 --> 00:58:51.920
Antigonus, when Demetrius returned and
made a detailed report of what he had

00:58:51.920 --> 00:58:56.559
done, rebuked him for the treaty with the
Nabataeans, saying that he had made the

00:58:56.559 --> 00:59:00.480
barbarians much bolder by leaving them
unpunished,

00:59:00.480 --> 00:59:04.400
since it would seem to them that they
had gained pardon not through his

00:59:04.400 --> 00:59:08.079
kindness
but through his inability to overcome

00:59:08.079 --> 00:59:10.319
them.

00:59:10.720 --> 00:59:16.160
This episode gives us a marvelous
glimpse of the unique survival strategy

00:59:16.160 --> 00:59:21.440
that the Nabataeans employed,
and shows how they built an empire not

00:59:21.440 --> 00:59:26.400
out of conquest and death,
but out of the trickle of fresh water

00:59:26.400 --> 00:59:32.640
from the desert rocks and the endless
clinking of silver pieces moving across

00:59:32.640 --> 00:59:36.880
the desert from hand to hand.

00:59:41.920 --> 00:59:48.319
In telling the story of the Nabataeans,
there will be one voice conspicuously

00:59:48.319 --> 00:59:52.160
missing,
and that is the voice of the Nabataeans

00:59:52.160 --> 00:59:55.839
themselves.
As far as we can tell,

00:59:55.839 --> 01:00:01.440
the Nabataeans had a good level of
literacy, and it seems even common people

01:00:01.440 --> 01:00:07.760
could read and write to some extent.
The Nabataean script is a kind of late

01:00:07.760 --> 01:00:13.359
Aramaic, ultimately derived from what's
called Imperial Aramaic, which was used

01:00:13.359 --> 01:00:18.400
by the Persian Empire.
We have evidence of graffiti written on

01:00:18.400 --> 01:00:24.319
stones all over the Jordanian desert,
some apparently left by shepherds who

01:00:24.319 --> 01:00:30.400
were capable of writing at least their
own names and some short inscriptions,

01:00:30.400 --> 01:00:36.400
but despite this apparently widespread
literacy, no histories or accounts

01:00:36.400 --> 01:00:40.000
actually written by Nabataeans have
survived.

01:00:40.000 --> 01:00:45.680
We may never know the reasons for this.
It's possible that the tribal roots of

01:00:45.680 --> 01:00:52.240
Nabataean society meant that they had
inherited a cast of oral historians and

01:00:52.240 --> 01:00:57.839
storytellers whose job it was to
memorize their histories and recite them,

01:00:57.839 --> 01:01:02.880
and that while these storytellers were
alive, it simply never seemed necessary

01:01:02.880 --> 01:01:08.400
to write those histories down.
It's possible that oral historians of

01:01:08.400 --> 01:01:13.760
this kind may even have jealously
guarded their histories, even forbidden

01:01:13.760 --> 01:01:19.760
them from being written down, in order to
preserve their own importance and status.

01:01:19.760 --> 01:01:25.200
But all of this is speculation, and for
the most part, all the Nabataeans have

01:01:25.200 --> 01:01:29.920
left us on this matter is silence.

01:01:31.440 --> 01:01:36.960
The almost complete lack of Nabataean
sources means that to tell their story,

01:01:36.960 --> 01:01:41.680
we are left searching through the
written records of other societies,

01:01:41.680 --> 01:01:46.880
looking for any mention of them.
These mentions are often brief and

01:01:46.880 --> 01:01:52.400
fragmentary, and form instantaneous
flashbulb moments in which the

01:01:52.400 --> 01:01:57.280
Nabataeans appear suddenly in the
historical record and then disappear

01:01:57.280 --> 01:02:03.359
again into darkness.
About fifty years after the incident with

01:02:03.359 --> 01:02:09.039
Antigonus the One-Eyed and his two
failed invasions of Nabataea, we get a

01:02:09.039 --> 01:02:14.799
colorful account from the papyrus
archives of an Egyptian politician named

01:02:14.799 --> 01:02:22.480
Zenon, a right-hand man to the minister
of finance in Ptolemaic Egypt around 259

01:02:22.480 --> 01:02:26.640
BC.
One papyrus gives the account of a

01:02:26.640 --> 01:02:31.920
chariot driver who had seen two of his
colleagues have an uncomfortable run-in

01:02:31.920 --> 01:02:37.359
with a group of Nabataeans.
These two Greek chariot drivers had

01:02:37.359 --> 01:02:42.960
apparently been moonlighting as human
traffickers, transporting slave girls and

01:02:42.960 --> 01:02:50.319
selling them in the cities they visited.
Memorandum to Zenon from Heraclides the

01:02:50.319 --> 01:02:55.119
charioteer,
regarding what was done by Drimylus and

01:02:55.119 --> 01:03:00.079
Dionysius to the slave girl,
abusing her and handing her over to a

01:03:00.079 --> 01:03:04.079
border guard.
Returning from there, he encountered the

01:03:04.079 --> 01:03:08.720
Nabataeans,
and when there was a shout of protest, he

01:03:08.720 --> 01:03:13.599
was put under guard and placed in
shackles for seven days.

01:03:13.599 --> 01:03:17.440
Concerning further details, if you
question me,

01:03:17.440 --> 01:03:21.520
you will learn the entire truth.

01:03:22.559 --> 01:03:28.799
This remarkable and enigmatic entry
leaves us with a lot of questions, but it

01:03:28.799 --> 01:03:33.520
shows that the Nabataeans were already
familiar figures right across the Middle

01:03:33.520 --> 01:03:36.000
East.
It's not clear what caused the

01:03:36.000 --> 01:03:41.039
Nabataeans to utter their shout of
protest and imprison these men.

01:03:41.039 --> 01:03:45.920
Perhaps it was some personal insult or a
dispute over trade,

01:03:45.920 --> 01:03:50.400
but some historians have wondered
whether it shows that the Nabataeans

01:03:50.400 --> 01:03:55.839
were offended by the men's treatment of
the women in their captivity and decided

01:03:55.839 --> 01:04:01.599
to dole out some justice of their own.
Nabataean culture seems to have held

01:04:01.599 --> 01:04:07.119
women in high regard, with queens
appearing alongside kings on certain

01:04:07.119 --> 01:04:12.559
coins, and with tomb inscriptions
describing women acting as the heads of

01:04:12.559 --> 01:04:16.640
households.
So, it's not far-fetched to imagine

01:04:16.640 --> 01:04:21.359
that the Greek's treatment of these
women may have offended the Nabataean's

01:04:21.359 --> 01:04:27.839
cultural sensibilities.
Another tantalizing flashbulb comes from

01:04:27.839 --> 01:04:32.480
the records of the Roman-Jewish
historian Flavius Josephus, in his

01:04:32.480 --> 01:04:38.480
account of the Jewish Maccabee revolt
against the Selucid Empire nearly a

01:04:38.480 --> 01:04:44.240
hundred years later.
The revolt was led by a Jewish priest

01:04:44.240 --> 01:04:50.400
named Judas Maccabeus, and at one point, he
and his brother Jonathan fled from

01:04:50.400 --> 01:04:56.480
Selucid forces across the river Jordan.
At this point, Josephus recounts how the

01:04:56.480 --> 01:05:01.760
brothers and their rebel forces ran into
a group of Nabataeans.

01:05:01.760 --> 01:05:07.039
These Nabataeans met them on friendly
terms and even warned them about

01:05:07.039 --> 01:05:13.920
atrocities that the Selucids had been
committing in a nearby Jewish settlement.

01:05:13.920 --> 01:05:18.480
Now, as for Judas Maccabeus and his
brother Jonathan,

01:05:18.480 --> 01:05:23.760
they passed over the river Jordan, and
when they had gone three day’s journey,

01:05:23.760 --> 01:05:28.640
they lighted upon the Nabataeans who
came to meet them peaceably,

01:05:28.640 --> 01:05:32.799
and who told them how the affairs of
those in the land of Gilead stood, and

01:05:32.799 --> 01:05:37.760
how many of them were in distress
and driven into garrisons and into the

01:05:37.760 --> 01:05:43.520
cities of Galilee, and exhorted him to
make haste, to go against the foreigners,

01:05:43.520 --> 01:05:48.160
and to endeavor to save his own
countrymen out of their hands.

01:05:48.160 --> 01:05:53.760
To this exhortation Judas hearkened and
returned to the wilderness,

01:05:53.760 --> 01:05:58.480
and in the first place
fell upon the inhabitants of Bosor and

01:05:58.480 --> 01:06:04.559
took the city.
Again, this fragmentary glimpse is

01:06:04.559 --> 01:06:09.200
fascinating but frustrating. The
Nabataeans seem to have had a

01:06:09.200 --> 01:06:14.720
long-standing friendly relationship with
the Judaean people and were apparently

01:06:14.720 --> 01:06:19.200
supportive of their rebellion.
It's possible that the Nabataeans,

01:06:19.200 --> 01:06:24.319
clearly valuing their own independence,
viewed the Judaean struggle for freedom

01:06:24.319 --> 01:06:29.119
with a great deal of sympathy.
But no doubt, they also enjoyed the

01:06:29.119 --> 01:06:34.880
opportunity to cause trouble for the
Selucid Empire, their powerful rivals to

01:06:34.880 --> 01:06:37.440
the north.

01:06:37.520 --> 01:06:43.119
An inscription at the archaeological
site of Haluza in the Negev Desert

01:06:43.119 --> 01:06:47.920
contains the first mention of the name
of a king of Nabataea.

01:06:47.920 --> 01:06:53.280
This inscription, written in a very early
form of Nabataean, says only the

01:06:53.280 --> 01:06:55.680
following.

01:06:55.920 --> 01:07:01.359
This is the place which Nuthairu made for
the life of King Aretas, king of the

01:07:01.359 --> 01:07:07.359
Nabataeans.
This King Aretas was the first king of

01:07:07.359 --> 01:07:12.799
Nabataea that we can definitively put a
name to, and it's clear that by this time,

01:07:12.799 --> 01:07:18.559
Nabataea was not just a tribal
confederacy but actually a kingdom.

01:07:18.559 --> 01:07:25.359
Half a century later, by the year 129 BC,
we get another flashbulb

01:07:25.359 --> 01:07:31.839
showing that Petra was now recognized as
a major regional capital.

01:07:32.079 --> 01:07:38.480
One inscription from a Greek ambassador
named Moschio son of Kydimos came from

01:07:38.480 --> 01:07:44.880
the city of Priene in modern day Turkey.
It recounts how Moschion traveled on

01:07:44.880 --> 01:07:50.079
diplomatic missions around the region,
and mentions two cities in the same

01:07:50.079 --> 01:07:54.400
breath;
the great city of Alexandria in Egypt,

01:07:54.400 --> 01:07:58.160
and the city of Petra.

01:07:58.880 --> 01:08:02.640
He acted as an envoy on behalf of the
people on many occasions,

01:08:02.640 --> 01:08:06.480
both to kings and to cities, and he
performed all these embassies to the

01:08:06.480 --> 01:08:10.400
advantage of the people.
The previous embassies he performed as a

01:08:10.400 --> 01:08:15.039
free gift, but when he was sent by his
fatherland on official business to king

01:08:15.039 --> 01:08:18.960
Ptolemaios in Alexandria and to Petra in
Arabia,

01:08:18.960 --> 01:08:25.279
he stayed there for a longer time that
had been anticipated by the people.

01:08:25.279 --> 01:08:30.640
It's clear that by this time, the tribal
peoples of Nabataea had grown into a

01:08:30.640 --> 01:08:36.239
true regional power and gained the
respect of their neighbors.

01:08:36.239 --> 01:08:41.359
They now directly controlled territory
across the Arabian Peninsula, into the

01:08:41.359 --> 01:08:46.960
Negev Desert, and across Palestine, but
their zone of influence stretched even

01:08:46.960 --> 01:08:50.480
further.
Their caravans arrived in countless

01:08:50.480 --> 01:08:56.640
cities laden with goods and crossed the
seas to trade with faraway lands,

01:08:56.640 --> 01:09:04.560
and as the power of the Nabataeans grew,
so did the magnificence of their stony

01:09:04.839 --> 01:09:10.799
capital. Petra was now a hive of
construction, with its people carving

01:09:10.799 --> 01:09:16.640
temples and tombs, directly imitating the
architectural styles of their powerful

01:09:16.640 --> 01:09:20.640
Greek neighbors.
It's around this time, during the

01:09:20.640 --> 01:09:25.839
first century BC, that the people of
Petra would construct the most

01:09:25.839 --> 01:09:31.359
impressive monument from their unique
culture of sandstone-carving.

01:09:31.359 --> 01:09:39.759
That's the enormous edifice known today
as the Khazneh, or the Great Treasury.

01:09:43.520 --> 01:09:50.000
The towering construction known as the
Khazneh is today one of the most famous

01:09:50.000 --> 01:09:54.400
buildings in the world.
It's thought to have been the mausoleum

01:09:54.400 --> 01:10:03.760
of a Nabataean king, possibly Aretas II,
Obodas III, or his successor, Aretas IV.

01:10:03.760 --> 01:10:10.000
But no inscriptions stand beside this
enormous carving to explain its purpose

01:10:10.000 --> 01:10:14.880
or who built it.
Today, the Khazneh stands as a silent

01:10:14.880 --> 01:10:20.320
testimony to the golden age of the
Nabataean kingdom, and it seems at every

01:10:20.320 --> 01:10:25.840
point to have been designed for maximum
impact on those who saw it.

01:10:25.840 --> 01:10:31.040
Ancient visitors to Petra would walk
along the narrow gully of the Siq,

01:10:31.040 --> 01:10:34.719
winding through the towering walls of
sandstone,

01:10:34.719 --> 01:10:40.080
and finally emerge into this spectacle
of sheer visual drama.

01:10:40.080 --> 01:10:45.760
The towering colonnades and galleries of
the facade, a sight that still has its

01:10:45.760 --> 01:10:49.520
intended impact on modern tourists to
this day,

01:10:49.520 --> 01:10:54.640
more than two millennia after its
designers walked the earth.

01:10:54.640 --> 01:10:59.679
At the time it was built, the ground
level beneath the Khazneh was about four

01:10:59.679 --> 01:11:05.360
meters lower than it is today, and a
steep staircase led up to its pillared

01:11:05.360 --> 01:11:09.040
doorway.
The design of the Khazneh marries the

01:11:09.040 --> 01:11:14.480
Nabataean art of stone carving with Greek
architectural styles,

01:11:14.480 --> 01:11:21.600
depicting Nabataean gods alongside Greek
deities like Tyche, god of fortune and

01:11:21.600 --> 01:11:28.880
cities, and Egyptian gods like Isis.
It's clear that in this hybrid style, the

01:11:28.880 --> 01:11:34.400
people of Petra were laying claim to a
status equal to the Greek empires that

01:11:34.400 --> 01:11:40.080
surrounded them, and marking their city
as one of the great metropolises of the

01:11:40.080 --> 01:11:43.840
world.
The monument was carved using iron

01:11:43.840 --> 01:11:49.440
pickaxes and chisels, and today you can
still see the marks left by the

01:11:49.440 --> 01:11:55.040
scaffolding of the workers who toiled
through endless hours and dangerous

01:11:55.040 --> 01:12:00.800
conditions to bring its perfect
proportions into existence.

01:12:00.800 --> 01:12:06.159
When the Khazneh was built, it would have
been remarkable to the citizens of Petra,

01:12:06.159 --> 01:12:10.000
who had never seen anything like it in
their city.

01:12:10.000 --> 01:12:14.880
But in the coming century, the building
would act as a model for several more

01:12:14.880 --> 01:12:19.360
monuments.
Among these are the stone facades known

01:12:19.360 --> 01:12:24.640
as the monastery, and another named the
Corinthian Tomb. But both of these

01:12:24.640 --> 01:12:30.800
monuments are smaller, less ambitious, and
less beautifully-proportioned than the

01:12:30.800 --> 01:12:34.960
towering facade of the Khazneh.

01:12:35.120 --> 01:12:40.400
Thanks to visitors who passed through in
the coming centuries, we do know a great

01:12:40.400 --> 01:12:45.840
amount about what the average citizen of
Petra would have experienced in their

01:12:45.840 --> 01:12:49.480
everyday life.

01:12:50.239 --> 01:12:55.760
The first century Greek writer and
geographer Strabo recounts the foods

01:12:55.760 --> 01:13:01.280
enjoyed by the Nabataeans.
Most of the country is well-supplied

01:13:01.280 --> 01:13:06.000
with fruits, except the olive. They use
sesame oil instead.

01:13:06.000 --> 01:13:11.040
The sheep are white-fleeced and the oxen
are large, but the country produces no

01:13:11.040 --> 01:13:14.320
horses.
Camels afford the service they require

01:13:14.320 --> 01:13:17.360
instead of horses.

01:13:17.520 --> 01:13:23.120
We can also find a reference to a
particular kind of fermented bread known

01:13:23.120 --> 01:13:29.600
as Khubz al-ma’ al-Nabati’, or Nabataean
water bread, in a 10th century cookbook

01:13:29.600 --> 01:13:32.880
by Ibn Sayyar al-Warraq.

01:13:34.000 --> 01:13:38.239
Take seven and a half pounds of good-
-quality samidh flour

01:13:38.239 --> 01:13:44.000
and sift it in a big wooden bowl.
Mix it with three ounces yeast and add

01:13:44.000 --> 01:13:49.040
three ounces salt that has been
dissolved in water and strained.

01:13:49.040 --> 01:13:55.199
Knead the mixture into a very firm dough,
as firm as stone, and press it well.

01:13:55.199 --> 01:14:00.239
Cover the dough and let it ferment.
With the help of some oil of hulled

01:14:00.239 --> 01:14:04.560
sesame seeds,
divide the dough into portions,

01:14:04.560 --> 01:14:08.000
light the tannur,
and wait until the fire starts to

01:14:08.000 --> 01:14:12.080
smolder gently.
Rub each portion of the dough with two

01:14:12.080 --> 01:14:16.159
dirhams sesame oil or olive oil,
then

01:14:16.159 --> 01:14:22.719
flatten it by hand and stick it to the
inside of a smoldering oven.

01:14:23.360 --> 01:14:27.600
It's likely that the Nabataeans would
have done their baking early in the

01:14:27.600 --> 01:14:30.719
morning,
before the heat of the day would make

01:14:30.719 --> 01:14:35.600
lighting a fire unbearable. We can
imagine the smoke of these fires

01:14:35.600 --> 01:14:40.640
drifting through the shaded gullies of
the city in the cool desert mornings, the

01:14:40.640 --> 01:14:47.520
smells of baking bread, yeast, and
sizzling sesame oil filling the air.

01:14:47.520 --> 01:14:52.400
According to sources of the time, walking
the streets of Petra would have been a

01:14:52.400 --> 01:14:57.679
colorful experience.
The writer Strabo recounts the many

01:14:57.679 --> 01:15:02.480
colored clothes of the city's
inhabitants and the many smells that

01:15:02.480 --> 01:15:08.400
would have wafted through the streets.
They go without tunics, with girdles

01:15:08.400 --> 01:15:12.880
around their loins and with slippers on
their feet, even the kings, though in

01:15:12.880 --> 01:15:17.520
their case the color is purple.
Some things are imported wholly from

01:15:17.520 --> 01:15:22.239
other countries, but others not
altogether so, especially in the case of

01:15:22.239 --> 01:15:27.760
those that are native products, as for
example, gold and silver, and most of the

01:15:27.760 --> 01:15:34.960
aromatics, whereas brass and iron, as
also purple garb, styrax, crocus, costaria,

01:15:34.960 --> 01:15:41.760
embossed works, paintings, and molded
works are not produced in their country.

01:15:41.760 --> 01:15:46.800
Nabataean religion revolved mostly
around the worship of a god named

01:15:46.800 --> 01:15:51.199
Dushara,
a kind of father god like the Greek Zeus,

01:15:51.199 --> 01:15:55.920
who was responsible for justice and
seems to have been associated with the

01:15:55.920 --> 01:16:00.159
sun.
He was often represented by simple

01:16:00.159 --> 01:16:06.320
square-shaped blocks of stone.
Nabataeans would apparently offer animal

01:16:06.320 --> 01:16:11.280
sacrifices to Dushara,
and would give him offerings in the form

01:16:11.280 --> 01:16:16.800
of Petra's most abundant trade commodity;
incense.

01:16:16.800 --> 01:16:21.520
They worship the sun, building an altar
on top of the house and pouring

01:16:21.520 --> 01:16:26.080
libations on it daily, and burning
frankincense.

01:16:26.080 --> 01:16:32.159
No doubt the temples of Petra would have
sent great clouds of frankincense, myrrh,

01:16:32.159 --> 01:16:39.040
and other aromatics wafting out into its
streets to mix with the smells of camels

01:16:39.040 --> 01:16:44.640
and goats, cooking food, and smoldering
charcoal ovens.

01:16:44.640 --> 01:16:50.560
Many of the peoples of Nabataea were
still transient, traveling constantly all

01:16:50.560 --> 01:16:55.840
year round from trade post to trade post.
But in order to maintain a sense of

01:16:55.840 --> 01:17:01.920
community, it seems they did all gather
every year for a kind of festival part

01:17:01.920 --> 01:17:06.800
market, part ceremony, and part feast
where the disparate tribes of the

01:17:06.800 --> 01:17:10.719
Nabataeans would come together to
exchange goods,

01:17:10.719 --> 01:17:15.600
talk, tell stories, and of course, drink
wine.

01:17:15.600 --> 01:17:20.400
Strabo describes the sights of one of
these Nabataean celebrations,

01:17:20.400 --> 01:17:25.920
and he's struck by the noticeable lack
of slavery in the city, something that

01:17:25.920 --> 01:17:31.840
would have been remarkable to someone
who lived in the Roman Empire.

01:17:31.840 --> 01:17:35.600
But when the time draws near for the
national gathering at which those who

01:17:35.600 --> 01:17:40.640
dwell round about are accustomed to meet,
they travel to this meeting, leaving on a

01:17:40.640 --> 01:17:45.520
certain rock their possessions and their
old men, also their women and their

01:17:45.520 --> 01:17:49.120
children.
Since they have but few slaves, they are

01:17:49.120 --> 01:17:54.719
served by their kinsfolk for the most
part or by one another, or by themselves

01:17:54.719 --> 01:17:59.920
so that the custom extends even to their
kings. They prepare common meals together

01:17:59.920 --> 01:18:05.520
in groups of thirteen persons, and they have
two girl singers for each banquet.

01:18:05.520 --> 01:18:10.560
The king holds many drinking bouts in
magnificent style, but no one drinks more

01:18:10.560 --> 01:18:15.360
than eleven cupfuls, each time using a
different golden cup.

01:18:15.360 --> 01:18:20.480
The king is so democratic that in
addition to serving himself, he sometimes

01:18:20.480 --> 01:18:25.560
even serves the rest himself in his turn.

01:18:28.400 --> 01:18:33.280
The fact that we have to largely rely on
the accounts of others when recreating

01:18:33.280 --> 01:18:38.159
the daily lives of the Nabataeans is
frustrating for any scholar of the

01:18:38.159 --> 01:18:43.520
period. But in fact, the Nabataeans did
leave behind one great body of

01:18:43.520 --> 01:18:48.719
literature; that's the inscriptions
carved into the stones of their great

01:18:48.719 --> 01:18:54.199
tombs in their own distinctive script.

01:18:54.320 --> 01:19:00.159
Many of the most complete of these can
be found at the site of Hegra, now in the

01:19:00.159 --> 01:19:07.920
northwest of modern Saudi Arabia.
Hegra was founded by the Nabataean king,

01:19:07.920 --> 01:19:15.199
Aretas IV, in the final years of the first
century BC, and he named it the kingdom's

01:19:15.199 --> 01:19:21.280
second capital.
In some ways, its carved tombs are more

01:19:21.280 --> 01:19:26.800
dramatic and impressive than those at
Petra, since they can be seen from great

01:19:26.800 --> 01:19:30.480
distances,
looming on the horizon of the flat

01:19:30.480 --> 01:19:34.719
desert plain.
The most famous of these is known in

01:19:34.719 --> 01:19:40.480
Arabic as Qasr al-Farid, or the Lonely
Castle.

01:19:40.480 --> 01:19:46.480
It is as finely carved as anything found
at Petra, and it forms a particularly

01:19:46.480 --> 01:19:50.480
haunting monument to the city that once
stood here,

01:19:50.480 --> 01:19:54.640
now buried beneath the sands.

01:19:54.800 --> 01:19:59.600
The tomb inscriptions of Hegra are
remarkable texts.

01:19:59.600 --> 01:20:03.679
Many of them are extremely weathered
since they have been exposed to the

01:20:03.679 --> 01:20:10.560
desert winds for more than 2,000 years,
but many are also perfectly clear and

01:20:10.560 --> 01:20:15.040
legible.
These tomb inscriptions often contain

01:20:15.040 --> 01:20:20.800
warnings of curses from the gods that
would land upon any tomb robbers, but

01:20:20.800 --> 01:20:25.520
they were also binding legal documents,
ensuring that the tomb remained the

01:20:25.520 --> 01:20:31.199
property of a single family down the
generations, with infractions punishable

01:20:31.199 --> 01:20:36.239
by fines.
This inscription from one Hegra tomb is

01:20:36.239 --> 01:20:41.199
a prime example of this hybrid form.

01:20:41.600 --> 01:20:47.120
This is the tomb and platform and
enclosure from which Hawshabu, son of

01:20:47.120 --> 01:20:52.639
Nafiyu, son of Alkuf the Taymanite, made
for himself and his children, and Habbu

01:20:52.639 --> 01:20:56.560
his mother,
and Rufu and Aftiyu, his sisters

01:20:56.560 --> 01:21:00.480
and their children --
inviolable according to the nature of

01:21:00.480 --> 01:21:05.440
inviolability among the Nabataeans and
Salamians forever,

01:21:05.440 --> 01:21:10.239
and may Dushara curse anybody who buries
in this tomb

01:21:10.239 --> 01:21:14.800
anyone except those inscribed above,
or sells it,

01:21:14.800 --> 01:21:19.040
or buys it, or gives it in pledge or
leases it,

01:21:19.040 --> 01:21:23.120
or makes a gift of it,
or disposes of it,

01:21:23.120 --> 01:21:26.400
and whoever does other than what is
written above

01:21:26.400 --> 01:21:32.480
shall be liable to the god Dushara
for the full price of a thousand Selas,

01:21:32.480 --> 01:21:37.440
and to our lord King Haretat
for the same amount.

01:21:37.440 --> 01:21:41.679
In the month of Shebat,
the 13th year of Haretite,

01:21:41.679 --> 01:21:47.040
king of the Nabataeans,
lover of his people.

01:21:48.239 --> 01:21:55.040
Inside the tomb, the niches are marked
with a shorter inscription.

01:21:55.280 --> 01:21:59.600
These are the two burial niches of
Hawshabu, son of Nafiyu,

01:21:59.600 --> 01:22:05.600
and Abdalga and Habbu, his children,
and may he who separates night from day

01:22:05.600 --> 01:22:10.040
curse whoever removes them forever.

01:22:10.159 --> 01:22:16.000
These tomb inscriptions all more or less
follow this format, and while they are

01:22:16.000 --> 01:22:21.679
limited in what they can teach us, they
do take on a remarkable significance and

01:22:21.679 --> 01:22:27.120
even poignancy when we consider that
these are the only texts left behind

01:22:27.120 --> 01:22:32.639
actually written by Nabataeans.
Theirs is a culture whose only surviving

01:22:32.639 --> 01:22:39.440
testament is their tombstones.
In these brief carved messages, we can

01:22:39.440 --> 01:22:43.840
learn little glimmers of information.

01:22:44.159 --> 01:22:48.800
We learn about the names of their gods
and get some sense of how they thought

01:22:48.800 --> 01:22:54.480
of them. We can hear Nabataean names, and
sometimes we can recreate their family

01:22:54.480 --> 01:22:58.320
trees, their wives and sisters and
children.

01:22:58.320 --> 01:23:03.840
We can hear hints of a society in which
the temple and the king both held some

01:23:03.840 --> 01:23:08.960
kind of independent authority,
and where a complex legal system was

01:23:08.960 --> 01:23:15.040
enforced with laws and fines.
In some of these inscriptions, credit is

01:23:15.040 --> 01:23:19.920
even given to the masons who carved the
tomb, giving some hint as to the

01:23:19.920 --> 01:23:26.400
importance that these artists held in
this city of stone.

01:23:26.639 --> 01:23:34.880
In the month of Nisan, the 36th year of
Haretite, king of the Nabataeans, love of his

01:23:34.880 --> 01:23:42.560
people, Aftah, son of Abdo-Bodat,
and Wahbu, son of Afsa, and Huru,

01:23:42.560 --> 01:23:46.880
the masons,
made this tomb.

01:23:46.880 --> 01:23:52.080
Since the professions of the people
buried in the tombs are usually listed,

01:23:52.080 --> 01:23:57.679
we also get a wonderful account of the
variety of ways that a Nabataean could

01:23:57.679 --> 01:24:03.935
make their living in the cities of Hegra
and Petra. Malkion the omen-diviner; Sullay

01:24:03.935 --> 01:24:15.292
the governor; Aydu the prefect; Manotu the exorcist priest;
Kahlan the physician; Sadallahi

01:24:15.292 --> 01:24:22.639
the centurion.

01:24:22.639 --> 01:24:28.400
All of these people lived full lives in
the streets and markets and houses of

01:24:28.400 --> 01:24:35.760
these cities. They had friends, families,
lovers, secrets, and dreams, and now all

01:24:35.760 --> 01:24:42.080
that is left are the faded inscriptions
in stone, slowly disappearing under the

01:24:42.080 --> 01:24:45.840
desert winds and rain.

01:24:49.280 --> 01:24:55.120
Despite their centuries of domination of
trade in this region, the Nabataeans

01:24:55.120 --> 01:25:00.400
would eventually encounter an enemy that
could neither be defeated nor bought

01:25:00.400 --> 01:25:05.040
off.
That was a growing imperial power based

01:25:05.040 --> 01:25:10.719
on a peninsula far off in the central
Mediterranean that would soon expand to

01:25:10.719 --> 01:25:15.280
its most enormous height,
encompassing the entire Mediterranean

01:25:15.280 --> 01:25:20.480
Sea
and the lands of Arabia beyond.

01:25:20.480 --> 01:25:25.400
That was the power of Rome.

01:25:36.320 --> 01:25:41.520
By the end of the first century BC, the
Roman Republic had given way to the

01:25:41.520 --> 01:25:46.239
Roman Empire, a confident expanding
military power.

01:25:46.239 --> 01:25:52.560
By this time, Rome had conquered Judaea
and installed a tyrannical puppet king,

01:25:52.560 --> 01:25:58.000
Herod the Great, to rule it as a colony.
In 30 BC,

01:25:58.000 --> 01:26:03.520
Rome also conquered the Greek kingdom of
Ptolemaic Egypt and brought Roman

01:26:03.520 --> 01:26:09.280
legions to the banks of the Nile.
Then, like so many empires before

01:26:09.280 --> 01:26:15.520
them, the Romans began to look hungrily
east to the rich lands of Nabataea

01:26:15.520 --> 01:26:20.679
and the incense fields of Arabia.

01:26:22.719 --> 01:26:30.239
Rome was an enormous consumer of incense.
Roman temples burned frankincense and

01:26:30.239 --> 01:26:35.840
myrrh as part of their rituals, and with
the rapid growth of the empire, these

01:26:35.840 --> 01:26:41.760
temples would now stretch across all of
Europe, from Tunisia to Scotland, from

01:26:41.760 --> 01:26:47.040
Morocco to Mesopotamia.
At the height of its trade, it's

01:26:47.040 --> 01:26:53.120
estimated that each year, well over a
million kilograms of frankincense was

01:26:53.120 --> 01:26:59.360
imported into the Roman Empire.
Considering the exorbitant 25%

01:26:59.360 --> 01:27:04.880
tax that the Nabataeans charged on this,
it's no wonder that the Romans soon

01:27:04.880 --> 01:27:10.080
began to consider ways of cutting out
the middleman and taking charge of the

01:27:10.080 --> 01:27:17.600
incense trade themselves.
In the year 26 BC, the new Roman emperor

01:27:17.600 --> 01:27:23.679
Augustus sent one of his prefects who
had been stationed in Roman Egypt to

01:27:23.679 --> 01:27:29.679
explore the south of Arabia, accompanied
with a small expeditionary force,

01:27:29.679 --> 01:27:35.360
and to establish new direct trade routes
with the people who lived there.

01:27:35.360 --> 01:27:40.159
This man's name was Aelius Gallus.

01:27:43.840 --> 01:27:50.560
The geographer Strabo recalls the
purpose of this expedition.

01:27:50.960 --> 01:27:55.600
Aelius Gallus conceived the purpose of
winning the Arabians over to himself,

01:27:55.600 --> 01:28:00.239
or of subjugating them.
Another consideration was the report

01:28:00.239 --> 01:28:04.800
which had prevailed from all time, that
they were very wealthy and that they

01:28:04.800 --> 01:28:09.280
sold aromatics and the most valuable
stones for gold and silver,

01:28:09.280 --> 01:28:14.960
but never expended with outsiders any
part of what they received in exchange,

01:28:14.960 --> 01:28:18.639
for he expected either to deal with
wealthy friends

01:28:18.639 --> 01:28:22.960
or to master wealthy enemies.

01:28:23.920 --> 01:28:29.520
Curiously, the Nabataeans seemed all too
eager to help the Romans on their

01:28:29.520 --> 01:28:32.960
expedition.
They even offered to send one of their

01:28:32.960 --> 01:28:37.679
own people as a guide.
He was encouraged also by the

01:28:37.679 --> 01:28:42.400
expectation of assistance from the
Nabataeans, since they were friendly and

01:28:42.400 --> 01:28:46.480
promised to cooperate with him in every
way.

01:28:46.480 --> 01:28:52.000
Considering that the Nabataeans stood to
lose a great deal if Gallus' expedition

01:28:52.000 --> 01:28:55.840
was a success,
the Romans should perhaps have been more

01:28:55.840 --> 01:29:02.480
suspicious of these offers of help,
but apparently they were not.

01:29:02.480 --> 01:29:08.320
The guide that the Nabataean king sent
to help this Roman expedition was a man

01:29:08.320 --> 01:29:15.040
named Syllaeus, a cunning politician high
up in the Nabataean establishment.

01:29:15.040 --> 01:29:21.360
Syllaeus faced an unenviable task;
he had to appear to cooperate with the

01:29:21.360 --> 01:29:26.880
Roman expedition so as not to arouse the
anger of the mighty empire, but the

01:29:26.880 --> 01:29:33.760
Nabataean king had made quite clear that
the expedition must be a failure.

01:29:33.760 --> 01:29:38.560
Trapped between the Romans and his own
king, Syllaeus must have experienced

01:29:38.560 --> 01:29:45.040
sleepless nights as he guided the Roman
army through the deserts of Arabia.

01:29:45.040 --> 01:29:50.320
Strabo recounts how the mission unfolded.

01:29:51.199 --> 01:29:55.280
Gallus set out on the expedition, but he
was deceived by the Nabataean

01:29:55.280 --> 01:30:00.719
administrator Syllaeus,
who, although he had promised to be guide

01:30:00.719 --> 01:30:04.560
on the march
and to supply all needs and to cooperate

01:30:04.560 --> 01:30:08.800
with him,
acted treacherously in all things

01:30:08.800 --> 01:30:12.400
and pointed out neither a safe voyage
along the coast

01:30:12.400 --> 01:30:17.040
nor a safe journey by land,
misguiding him through places that had

01:30:17.040 --> 01:30:20.400
no roads
and by circuitous routes,

01:30:20.400 --> 01:30:23.600
and through regions destitute of
everything,

01:30:23.600 --> 01:30:28.239
or along rocky shores that had no
harbors or through waters that were

01:30:28.239 --> 01:30:33.840
shallow or full of submarine rocks,
and particularly in places of that kind

01:30:33.840 --> 01:30:37.679
the flood tides,
and also the ebb tides

01:30:37.679 --> 01:30:41.520
caused very great distress.

01:30:42.159 --> 01:30:47.920
It's clear that at every turn, the
Nabataean Syllaeus worked to frustrate

01:30:47.920 --> 01:30:55.600
and weaken Aelius Gallus' expedition,
using every deception available to him.

01:30:55.600 --> 01:31:01.440
After many experiences and hardships, he
arrived in 14 days at Leuke Kome, in the

01:31:01.440 --> 01:31:05.600
land of the Nabataeans, although he had
lost many of his boats,

01:31:05.600 --> 01:31:10.639
some of these being lost, crews and all,
on accounts of difficult sailing,

01:31:10.639 --> 01:31:16.239
but not on account of any enemy.
This was caused by the treachery of

01:31:16.239 --> 01:31:19.600
Syllaeus,
who said that there was no way for an

01:31:19.600 --> 01:31:24.080
army to go to Leuke Kome by land,
and yet,

01:31:24.080 --> 01:31:27.840
camel traders travel back and forth from
Petra to this place

01:31:27.840 --> 01:31:32.000
in safety
and ease.

01:31:32.480 --> 01:31:38.880
The expedition of Aelius Gallus would
take six months to work its weary way up

01:31:38.880 --> 01:31:45.040
the coast of southern Arabia, suffering
from disease, shipwrecks, even eating

01:31:45.040 --> 01:31:50.880
poisoned herbs and drinking tainted
water, so that the soldiers suffered from

01:31:50.880 --> 01:31:55.280
sickness and disease.
They would travel around in circles

01:31:55.280 --> 01:32:00.880
across the stony desert wastes, and take
the longest possible routes along rough

01:32:00.880 --> 01:32:04.960
terrain, baking in the searing Arabian
sun,

01:32:04.960 --> 01:32:11.520
suffering from heat stroke and fatigue.
Finally, with only a fraction of his

01:32:11.520 --> 01:32:16.480
original force remaining, Gallus was
forced to admit defeat.

01:32:16.480 --> 01:32:21.440
Although he was within reach of his goal,
he now feared that if he pushed on, none

01:32:21.440 --> 01:32:26.560
of them would survive, and he feared that
the journey home would take another six

01:32:26.560 --> 01:32:30.400
months.
He ordered his men to turn around

01:32:30.400 --> 01:32:35.840
and march back along the desert roads,
and it's only on the way home that he

01:32:35.840 --> 01:32:40.960
realized the trick that had been played
on him.

01:32:40.960 --> 01:32:45.679
He was indeed only two days’ journey from
the country that produced aromatics, as

01:32:45.679 --> 01:32:50.080
informed by his captives,
but he used up six months’ time on his

01:32:50.080 --> 01:32:54.480
marches because of bad guidance,
and he realized the fact when he turned

01:32:54.480 --> 01:32:57.199
back,
when at last he had learned the plot

01:32:57.199 --> 01:33:01.280
against him and had gone back by other
roads.

01:33:01.280 --> 01:33:06.080
On his return, he accomplished the whole
journey within sixty days.

01:33:06.080 --> 01:33:10.800
He'd used up six months in his first
journey.

01:33:14.480 --> 01:33:19.920
It's not recorded whether Syllaeus stuck
around to face the anger of the Roman

01:33:19.920 --> 01:33:24.400
commander or whether he slunk away in
the night.

01:33:24.400 --> 01:33:30.159
Strabo recounts the sorry sight of the
expedition as it returned to its base in

01:33:30.159 --> 01:33:34.440
Alexandria, empty-handed.

01:33:34.560 --> 01:33:38.880
Thence he carried his army across the Myus
Harbor within eleven days,

01:33:38.880 --> 01:33:44.159
and with all who had been fortunate
enough to survive, landed in Alexandria.

01:33:44.159 --> 01:33:48.719
The rest he had lost
not in wars, but from sickness and

01:33:48.719 --> 01:33:55.280
fatigue, and hunger and bad roads,
for only seven men perished in war.

01:33:55.280 --> 01:34:00.560
For these reasons, this expedition did
not profit us to a great extent in our

01:34:00.560 --> 01:34:05.000
knowledge of these regions.

01:34:06.159 --> 01:34:12.480
For his part, Syllaeus seems to have
returned to Petra to a hero's welcome.

01:34:12.480 --> 01:34:18.719
The failure of this disastrous
expedition set Rome back significantly.

01:34:18.719 --> 01:34:24.320
The empire would soon be convulsed by
civil wars, and was soon far too

01:34:24.320 --> 01:34:29.600
distracted to think about expanding any
further into Arabia.

01:34:29.600 --> 01:34:36.000
Syllaeus' actions would buy his people
more than a century of independence, but

01:34:36.000 --> 01:34:41.280
Rome's civil wars would not last forever,
and for the kingdom of Nabataea, the

01:34:41.280 --> 01:34:46.880
writing was on the wall.
As the first millennium BC became the

01:34:46.880 --> 01:34:53.760
first millennium AD, Rome officially
absorbed Judaea, Mesopotamia, and Syria

01:34:53.760 --> 01:34:59.360
into its enormous empire.
Nabataea gradually found itself

01:34:59.360 --> 01:35:05.199
surrounded by this overwhelming power,
and the era of its existence as an

01:35:05.199 --> 01:35:11.560
independent kingdom was soon to come to
an end.

01:35:17.840 --> 01:35:23.840
The last king of the Nabataeans was a
man named Rabbel II,

01:35:23.840 --> 01:35:31.360
who had ruled for thirty-six years.
When he died in the year 106 AD, the

01:35:31.360 --> 01:35:37.360
Roman emperor Trajan ordered two legions
to march into the region and capture the

01:35:37.360 --> 01:35:41.760
lands of Nabataea.
There doesn't seem to have been any

01:35:41.760 --> 01:35:48.639
particular pretext for the invasion;
Rabbel had a legitimate heir named Obodas

01:35:48.639 --> 01:35:53.280
who was ready to take the throne, but
it's clear that Rome didn't want to

01:35:53.280 --> 01:35:57.760
waste its opening.
The man who led this campaign was the

01:35:57.760 --> 01:36:02.639
Roman governor of Syria, a man named
Cornelius Palma.

01:36:02.639 --> 01:36:09.280
Under his command, the Third Cyrenaica
legion moves north from Egypt into Petra,

01:36:09.280 --> 01:36:15.600
while the Sixth Ferrata legion, a Syrian
garrison unit, moved south to occupy the

01:36:15.600 --> 01:36:20.480
town of Bostra.
As far as we can tell, the Romans faced

01:36:20.480 --> 01:36:24.159
little resistance.
In fact, the campaign was so

01:36:24.159 --> 01:36:29.760
underwhelming that the Roman historian
Cassius Dio, normally a colorful and

01:36:29.760 --> 01:36:35.199
detailed writer, had only the following
to say about it.

01:36:35.199 --> 01:36:40.560
About this time,
Palma, the governor of Syria, subdued the

01:36:40.560 --> 01:36:46.480
part of Arabia around Petra and made it
subject to the Romans.

01:36:46.480 --> 01:36:52.719
This sparse report is wedged in between
colorful accounts of Trajan's campaigns

01:36:52.719 --> 01:36:58.639
against the Dacians and his spectacles
involving 10,000 gladiators.

01:36:58.639 --> 01:37:03.440
Even the Roman coins minted to celebrate
the victory seem to reflect the

01:37:03.440 --> 01:37:09.280
understated nature of the campaign. They
were marked with the words ‘Arabia

01:37:09.280 --> 01:37:13.679
adquisita’
rather than the more normal ‘capta’.

01:37:13.679 --> 01:37:20.000
For the Romans, Arabia had not been
captured, but simply acquired.

01:37:20.000 --> 01:37:25.520
Some units of the Nabataean's elite royal
guard do seem to have resisted the

01:37:25.520 --> 01:37:29.440
invaders,
but for the most part, the regular troops

01:37:29.440 --> 01:37:36.400
saw no point in fighting the inevitable.
Roman legions marched into Petra, and the

01:37:36.400 --> 01:37:42.400
age of Nabataean independence finally
came to an end.

01:37:42.719 --> 01:37:48.320
Rome would name the province they
founded there Arabia Petraea after the

01:37:48.320 --> 01:37:54.760
great city, and the period of Roman Petra
began.

01:38:02.320 --> 01:38:06.880
From what we can tell, it seems that for
the average citizen of the Nabataean

01:38:06.880 --> 01:38:12.639
kingdom, the annexation by Rome had
little effect on their lives, at least at

01:38:12.639 --> 01:38:17.760
first.
The historian Jane Taylor describes the

01:38:17.760 --> 01:38:22.560
situation.
It was only the top management that

01:38:22.560 --> 01:38:26.800
changed, the governors and a handful of
officials.

01:38:26.800 --> 01:38:31.760
In due course, the old royal army was
absorbed into the Roman auxiliary forces

01:38:31.760 --> 01:38:37.600
as six portraying cohorts,
a total of 6,000 men.

01:38:37.600 --> 01:38:42.800
As for the non-military majority,
landowners, stonemasons, ceramicists,

01:38:42.800 --> 01:38:49.360
scribes, priests, musicians, jugglers, or
minor officials, most stayed where they

01:38:49.360 --> 01:38:52.880
were, paid their taxes to the new
authority,

01:38:52.880 --> 01:39:00.320
and pursued the accustomed daily pattern
of their lives, more or less unchanged.

01:39:00.800 --> 01:39:05.920
Usually when Rome captured an area, they
would set about immediately building new

01:39:05.920 --> 01:39:11.679
aqueducts and water systems,
but conspicuously in Petra, they left the

01:39:11.679 --> 01:39:15.600
Nabataean water system virtually
untouched.

01:39:15.600 --> 01:39:21.040
This suggests that they saw little room
for improvement to the already skillful

01:39:21.040 --> 01:39:23.679
engineering.

01:39:24.560 --> 01:39:29.199
To ensure the security of their new
conquest and perhaps with bitter

01:39:29.199 --> 01:39:35.040
memories of Aelius Gallus' expedition
still in their minds, the Romans built a

01:39:35.040 --> 01:39:41.600
highway through the entire territory.
They named this the Via Nova Traiana, or

01:39:41.600 --> 01:39:47.840
Trajan's New Road, a 400-kilometer
highway connecting Petra and Bostra to

01:39:47.840 --> 01:39:54.560
the sea port of Aqaba on the Red Sea.
The road was lined with forts, ensuring a

01:39:54.560 --> 01:40:00.400
permanent control of the trade routes, to
the rich incense fields of the south,

01:40:00.400 --> 01:40:06.000
and meaning that the Romans could now
move their forces with ease.

01:40:06.000 --> 01:40:12.719
One Roman citizen, Aelius Aristides, who
lived during the second century AD

01:40:12.719 --> 01:40:18.239
in the Roman province of Asia, wrote the
following description of the times and

01:40:18.239 --> 01:40:24.320
shows that the Romans believed that the
uncontrollable lands of Arabia had

01:40:24.320 --> 01:40:30.320
finally been pacified.
Wars have so far vanished as to be

01:40:30.320 --> 01:40:35.440
legendary affairs of the past.
Now, a man simply travels from one

01:40:35.440 --> 01:40:39.679
country to another as though it were his
native land.

01:40:39.679 --> 01:40:44.320
We are no longer frightened by the
Cilician Pass or by the narrow, sandy

01:40:44.320 --> 01:40:49.360
tracks that lead from Arabia to Egypt.
We are not dismayed by the height of

01:40:49.360 --> 01:40:54.080
mountains or by the vast breadth of
rivers or by inhospitable tribes or

01:40:54.080 --> 01:40:58.480
barbarians.
To be a Roman citizen is a sufficient

01:40:58.480 --> 01:41:02.639
guarantee of personal safety.

01:41:02.960 --> 01:41:08.880
For the city of Petra, the period of
Roman annexation would be the beginning

01:41:08.880 --> 01:41:13.600
of the end.
Over the coming centuries, Petra would

01:41:13.600 --> 01:41:19.920
ultimately be undone by cultural and
economic shifts that swept the whole

01:41:19.920 --> 01:41:23.520
world along with them.

01:41:28.080 --> 01:41:34.159
In the third and fourth centuries, the
Roman Empire would undergo some dramatic

01:41:34.159 --> 01:41:39.119
changes.
The cult of Jesus Christ, once a small

01:41:39.119 --> 01:41:44.880
fringe group of worshipers based around
the veneration of an executed Jewish

01:41:44.880 --> 01:41:49.840
prophet, had grown to become a real
threat to Roman power.

01:41:49.840 --> 01:41:55.440
For a time, Christianity was outlawed in
the empire, and during the reign of the

01:41:55.440 --> 01:42:01.280
emperor Diocletian, records show that the
Christians of Petra were punished for

01:42:01.280 --> 01:42:08.560
their refusal to sacrifice to Roman gods.
Many of them were sent to die by forced

01:42:08.560 --> 01:42:13.840
labor in the nearby Roman copper mines
of Phaino.

01:42:13.840 --> 01:42:19.360
Christianity was finally adopted by the
emperor Constantine, and would become the

01:42:19.360 --> 01:42:23.119
major belief system of the late Roman
Empire.

01:42:23.119 --> 01:42:28.960
But as Christian modes of worship spread,
the way that people conducted ceremonies

01:42:28.960 --> 01:42:33.040
also changed,
and this would have a dramatic effect on

01:42:33.040 --> 01:42:40.040
the commodities that people consumed and
on the people of Petra.

01:42:43.040 --> 01:42:48.480
While today we think of incense as an
integral part of worship in the Catholic

01:42:48.480 --> 01:42:53.920
and orthodox churches, early Christians
were keen to emphasize the difference

01:42:53.920 --> 01:42:57.520
between themselves and the old pagan
temples.

01:42:57.520 --> 01:43:03.600
For this reason, Christians at this time
did not use incense in their ceremonies.

01:43:03.600 --> 01:43:09.920
As pagan temples were shut down, demand
for incense crashed, and the price began

01:43:09.920 --> 01:43:14.480
to fall.
This broader cultural and economic

01:43:14.480 --> 01:43:21.199
change came at the same time as Egyptian
ports began to supersede the land-based

01:43:21.199 --> 01:43:25.840
trade routes for incense, spices, and
silks.

01:43:25.840 --> 01:43:30.800
As an independent kingdom, the Nabataeans
had jealously guarded their source of

01:43:30.800 --> 01:43:36.639
frankincense, but with Nabataea conquered,
the Romans began extracting incense by

01:43:36.639 --> 01:43:42.159
the more efficient route; carrying goods
by sea to Egypt rather than on the

01:43:42.159 --> 01:43:47.440
arduous desert roads by land.
As a result, the very thing that the

01:43:47.440 --> 01:43:54.080
Nabataeans had feared came to pass.
The importance of Petra as a trading hub

01:43:54.080 --> 01:43:57.119
began to fall.

01:44:03.760 --> 01:44:09.440
Although it had given its name to the
province of Arabia Petraea, the Romans

01:44:09.440 --> 01:44:13.920
also seemed to have had little use for
the Rose City.

01:44:13.920 --> 01:44:19.280
The very things that had made Petra
attractive to the Nabataeans, that is how

01:44:19.280 --> 01:44:25.280
remote, hidden, and difficult to reach it
was, made it an unattractive place for a

01:44:25.280 --> 01:44:30.560
Roman administration which needed good
links to the capital. The Romans

01:44:30.560 --> 01:44:34.800
increasingly conducted the running of
the province from the more northern and

01:44:34.800 --> 01:44:40.239
well-connected town of Bostra,
and the prominence of Petra as the

01:44:40.239 --> 01:44:45.360
administrative center of the region fell
even further.

01:44:45.360 --> 01:44:49.760
Petra at this time must have been a sad
place.

01:44:49.760 --> 01:44:55.440
The former markets and workshops that
had once boomed with life and noise must

01:44:55.440 --> 01:45:02.400
have grown smaller every year as fewer
and fewer caravans passed through. The

01:45:02.400 --> 01:45:08.560
fine cliffside houses, where once
children ran and played, where families

01:45:08.560 --> 01:45:11.520
hung up their laundry and watched the
sunset,

01:45:11.520 --> 01:45:18.400
would have become abandoned one by one,
home only to desert bats and wild dogs

01:45:18.400 --> 01:45:21.679
that would have howled to one another at
night

01:45:21.679 --> 01:45:29.040
in the gradually emptying valleys.
Despite its declining importance, Petra

01:45:29.040 --> 01:45:34.639
may still have continued as an important
trading spot were it not for the events

01:45:34.639 --> 01:45:41.520
of the 18th of May, in the year 363
AD.

01:45:43.280 --> 01:45:48.320
It was the middle of the night when the
first tremors began,

01:45:48.320 --> 01:45:54.560
a shuddering and shaking in the earth,
accompanied by a low rumble.

01:45:54.560 --> 01:45:58.400
Somewhere deep in the faultline of the
Red Sea,

01:45:58.400 --> 01:46:04.239
the edges of the African and Arabian
Plates gave way against one another, and

01:46:04.239 --> 01:46:08.400
an earthquake shook the region.

01:46:08.960 --> 01:46:14.880
This would be known as the Galilee
Earthquake, a pair of severe tremors on

01:46:14.880 --> 01:46:23.280
the 18th and 19th of May in the year 363.
One letter, thought to be written by the

01:46:23.280 --> 01:46:30.480
bishop Cyril of Jerusalem, recalls the
tremendous impact of the earthquake.

01:46:30.480 --> 01:46:35.119
This event took place on Monday at the
third hour,

01:46:35.119 --> 01:46:38.639
and partly at the ninth hour of the
night.

01:46:38.639 --> 01:46:43.520
There was a great loss of life here.
The land was shaken

01:46:43.520 --> 01:46:49.679
and mighty prodigies took place,
and fire consumed great numbers of them.

01:46:49.679 --> 01:46:54.800
The land shook considerably and there
were great tremors in the towns round

01:46:54.800 --> 01:46:58.480
about.
Many Christians, too, living in these

01:46:58.480 --> 01:47:04.960
regions, as well as the majority of the
Jews, perished at that scourge, and not

01:47:04.960 --> 01:47:10.080
just in the earthquake,
but also as a result of fire and in the

01:47:10.080 --> 01:47:13.600
heavy rain they had.

01:47:14.880 --> 01:47:20.639
Cyril goes on to list the settlements
most damaged by the tremors, and notes

01:47:20.639 --> 01:47:25.600
that more than half of the city of Petra
was destroyed.

01:47:25.600 --> 01:47:29.840
Now we should like to write down for you
the names of the towns that were

01:47:29.840 --> 01:47:32.880
overthrown;
Beit Gubrin,

01:47:32.880 --> 01:47:39.600
more than half of it, part of Baishan, the
whole of Sebastia and its territory, the

01:47:39.600 --> 01:47:46.080
whole of Nikopolis and its territory,
more than half of Petra, part of Tiberias,

01:47:46.080 --> 01:47:48.560
too,
and its territory.

01:47:48.560 --> 01:47:56.560
Haifa flowed with blood for three days.
Another chronicler named Thomas from the

01:47:56.560 --> 01:48:02.080
Rhesaina region wrote the following
account, in which he views the earthquake

01:48:02.080 --> 01:48:09.119
as a punishment from god for the
continuing pagan worship in the region.

01:48:09.679 --> 01:48:15.119
At that time, the Lord was angry with the
cities of the pagans and Jews and the

01:48:15.119 --> 01:48:20.000
Samaritans and of the false teachings in
the south that are joined in with the

01:48:20.000 --> 01:48:24.800
madness of the pagan Julian,
and anger went out from the Lord's

01:48:24.800 --> 01:48:29.760
presence and began to destroy the
unclean and pagan cities because they

01:48:29.760 --> 01:48:35.119
had defiled them with blood which they
shed unjustly in them.

01:48:35.119 --> 01:48:40.960
It began to destroy the cities, 21 in
number, some of which were overturned,

01:48:40.960 --> 01:48:47.600
some collapsed, and yet others survived
in the month of Iyyar, of the year 674,

01:48:47.600 --> 01:48:53.280
and on the 27th day in that month, in the
month of Haziran.

01:48:53.440 --> 01:48:58.719
Archaeological evidence in Petra
supports the picture of a sudden and

01:48:58.719 --> 01:49:02.239
devastating disaster.

01:49:04.239 --> 01:49:10.159
One house excavated by archaeologists
was reduced to a pile of rubble around

01:49:10.159 --> 01:49:14.400
this time.
Beneath the collapsed roof, a great

01:49:14.400 --> 01:49:17.920
number of everyday domestic items were
found;

01:49:17.920 --> 01:49:22.080
lamps,
shattered ceramics and glass, spindles

01:49:22.080 --> 01:49:27.360
and coins,
even a copper pot with an iron handle.

01:49:27.360 --> 01:49:34.239
Near the door, a smashed pot contained 85
small-denomination copper coins,

01:49:34.239 --> 01:49:38.159
apparently kept there for everyday
expenses.

01:49:38.159 --> 01:49:42.719
The fact that these were never reclaimed
or even looted

01:49:42.719 --> 01:49:47.840
suggests that the damage in the city was
too great for its declining population

01:49:47.840 --> 01:49:52.400
to even pick through,
let alone rebuild from.

01:49:52.400 --> 01:49:58.639
Many of Petra's great public buildings
were severely hit by the earthquake.

01:49:58.639 --> 01:50:04.480
The so-called Temple of the Winged Lions,
the building known as the Great Temple,

01:50:04.480 --> 01:50:11.840
and the public theater were all damaged,
and they would never be repaired.

01:50:12.800 --> 01:50:17.599
Particularly devastating seems to have
been the earthquake's effect on the

01:50:17.599 --> 01:50:23.119
city's water systems.
Subterranean pipes were cracked and

01:50:23.119 --> 01:50:28.560
would have leaked their precious water
into the sands, and some of its aqueducts

01:50:28.560 --> 01:50:32.719
split open.
Dams designed to hold in reservoirs of

01:50:32.719 --> 01:50:38.800
rainwater collapsed, causing widespread
flooding and severely depleting the

01:50:38.800 --> 01:50:43.840
city's supplies.
Petra's capacity to support life was

01:50:43.840 --> 01:50:49.679
directly linked to its capacity to store
water, and with the complicated system

01:50:49.679 --> 01:50:55.920
now coming apart at the seams, its water
and the city's remaining life would now

01:50:55.920 --> 01:51:00.719
leach away into the dust of the desert.

01:51:00.800 --> 01:51:06.320
It's clear that some of Petra's people
did creep back to repopulate the city

01:51:06.320 --> 01:51:10.719
after the earthquake.
In the area known as the Colonnaded

01:51:10.719 --> 01:51:16.239
Street, archaeology shows that some of
the earthquake debris was cleared away,

01:51:16.239 --> 01:51:21.760
and a shanty town of simple shops and
shelters was built out of material

01:51:21.760 --> 01:51:26.480
reclaimed from the rubble.
But the destruction of the city's water

01:51:26.480 --> 01:51:32.159
system meant that the annual flash
floods were no longer being controlled.

01:51:32.159 --> 01:51:37.840
We can see the evidence of these floods
in the build-up of silt and sand in the

01:51:37.840 --> 01:51:43.119
floors of these humble buildings,
as the waters crash down from the rocks

01:51:43.119 --> 01:51:49.199
in the rainy season, flooding everyone's
homes, and then giving way to months of

01:51:49.199 --> 01:51:54.239
punishing drought.
Some domestic structures were rebuilt

01:51:54.239 --> 01:51:58.560
after the earthquake,
and it's clear people tried to continue

01:51:58.560 --> 01:52:02.800
their lives.
They even constructed some new churches,

01:52:02.800 --> 01:52:07.679
although they were largely built from
material scavenged from other destroyed

01:52:07.679 --> 01:52:11.679
monuments.
But in the early 5th century, another

01:52:11.679 --> 01:52:18.400
earthquake struck and after that, most of
the grand houses were abandoned for good.

01:52:18.400 --> 01:52:27.440
The dream of Petra had died, and the city
gradually fell into disrepair and ruin.

01:52:27.440 --> 01:52:33.199
Despite all of this damage, people did
continue to live in reduced numbers

01:52:33.199 --> 01:52:38.159
around the ruins of Petra,
and it would continue as a humble

01:52:38.159 --> 01:52:43.679
caravan stop for several more centuries.
People continued to live in the

01:52:43.679 --> 01:52:49.119
hollowed-out cave houses,
and farmed on the terraces of its hills

01:52:49.119 --> 01:52:55.520
right up to the modern era.
As the Eastern Roman Empire morphed into

01:52:55.520 --> 01:53:01.520
the Byzantine Empire, the old city of
Petra was even named the capital of the

01:53:01.520 --> 01:53:07.679
province of Palaestina Tertia,
and several churches were built in and

01:53:07.679 --> 01:53:12.560
around the city.
In one of them, 140 papyruses were

01:53:12.560 --> 01:53:19.440
discovered, which contained mainly
contracts dated up to the year 590,

01:53:19.440 --> 01:53:22.960
showing that people were still living in
the city.

01:53:22.960 --> 01:53:27.920
According to the writer John Moschus,
Petra even had a bishop in the first

01:53:27.920 --> 01:53:32.800
decades of the 7th century, a man named
Athenogenes.

01:53:32.800 --> 01:53:38.960
But some time before the year 687,
the declining fortunes of the city meant

01:53:38.960 --> 01:53:45.440
that the position ceased to exist.
When Arab armies, inspired by the new

01:53:45.440 --> 01:53:51.280
faith of Islam and the teachings of the
prophet Muhammad swept across the region,

01:53:51.280 --> 01:53:56.080
Petra doesn't seem to have featured in
their interests at all. It's not

01:53:56.080 --> 01:54:01.440
mentioned once in the narratives of the
Muslim conquest, and nor does it appear

01:54:01.440 --> 01:54:07.679
in any early Islamic records.
As power in this region underwent

01:54:07.679 --> 01:54:11.199
another
of its great reshufflings, it seems the

01:54:11.199 --> 01:54:15.760
city of Petra was finally abandoned for
good.

01:54:15.760 --> 01:54:20.880
The Arabic that these new rulers spoke
was directly descended from the old

01:54:20.880 --> 01:54:27.119
Nabataean spoken by the ancient peoples
of Petra, but to these new conquerors, the

01:54:27.119 --> 01:54:33.840
Rose City was an irrelevance, a city of
tombs and ruins lost among the desert

01:54:33.840 --> 01:54:36.840
stones.

01:54:36.880 --> 01:54:42.239
The Muslims who came after and built
their own empires in the region were

01:54:42.239 --> 01:54:47.040
struck by the incredible sight of these
monumental stones

01:54:47.040 --> 01:54:51.520
still left at the sites of Hegra and
Petra.

01:54:51.520 --> 01:54:57.599
To explain them, they told stories about
a tribe that they called the Thamud, who

01:54:57.599 --> 01:55:02.840
were punished by god for refusing to
listen to a prophet named

01:55:02.840 --> 01:55:09.920
Salih. One version of this is given in
the Quran, in the Surah Al-A’raf,

01:55:09.920 --> 01:55:13.760
or the Chapter of the Heights.

01:55:15.599 --> 01:55:18.639
And they flouted the commandment of
their lord,

01:55:18.639 --> 01:55:21.440
and they said,
oh Salih,

01:55:21.440 --> 01:55:26.639
bring upon us that thou threatenest
if thou art indeed of those sent from

01:55:26.639 --> 01:55:30.320
Allah.
So the earthquake seized them,

01:55:30.320 --> 01:55:34.320
and morning found them prostrate in their
dwelling place.

01:55:34.320 --> 01:55:38.080
And Salih
turned from them and said,

01:55:38.080 --> 01:55:42.960
oh my people, I delivered my lord's
message unto you and gave you good

01:55:42.960 --> 01:55:48.159
advice,
but ye love not good advisors.

01:55:48.159 --> 01:55:52.800
As for the earth, we spread it out and
placed it upon its firm mountains

01:55:52.800 --> 01:55:56.400
and caused everything to grow there in
perfect balance.

01:55:56.400 --> 01:56:00.400
We made in it means of sustenance for
you and others.

01:56:00.400 --> 01:56:05.520
We send fertilizing winds and bring down
rain from the sky for you to drink.

01:56:05.520 --> 01:56:10.320
But the residents of the stone valley
also denied the messengers.

01:56:10.320 --> 01:56:15.520
We gave them our signs,
but they turned away from them.

01:56:15.520 --> 01:56:20.159
They carved their homes in the mountains,
feeling secure,

01:56:20.159 --> 01:56:23.920
but the mighty blast overtook them in
the morning,

01:56:23.920 --> 01:56:29.280
and all they achieved
was of no help to them.

01:56:29.280 --> 01:56:34.560
For these later people, the towering
ruins of the Nabataean cities became

01:56:34.560 --> 01:56:40.560
warnings about excessive pride, and a
reminder that the power of nature or the

01:56:40.560 --> 01:56:46.080
power of god can always undo the works
of man.

01:56:46.080 --> 01:56:51.360
For others, the ruins inspired poetry.

01:56:53.440 --> 01:56:59.440
I want to end the episode with a reading
from one of the great pre-Islamic poets,

01:56:59.440 --> 01:57:04.960
a man named Tarafa.
He wrote poetry that responded to the

01:57:04.960 --> 01:57:11.199
ruined sights that littered the horizon
of the Arab Peninsula left by peoples

01:57:11.199 --> 01:57:16.239
like the Nabataeans.
In this poem, he describes how the sight

01:57:16.239 --> 01:57:20.639
of these ruins
leads him to think about the transience

01:57:20.639 --> 01:57:26.480
and the injustice of life.
As you listen, imagine what it would feel

01:57:26.480 --> 01:57:32.960
like to live in the great city of Petra
during its final days, to watch the life

01:57:32.960 --> 01:57:38.960
slowly ebb from the city around you, as
the caravans arrived in fewer and fewer

01:57:38.960 --> 01:57:43.840
numbers across the sands.
Imagine the earthquakes cracking the

01:57:43.840 --> 01:57:50.320
great stones of the city, the feeling of
hopelessness as the water systems broke,

01:57:50.320 --> 01:57:54.800
and no one left knew how to repair them,
as people

01:57:54.800 --> 01:58:00.639
departed across the desert to begin new
lives in other places.

01:58:00.639 --> 01:58:07.119
Imagine watching the sands creep in to
cover the streets, the homes, and markets,

01:58:07.119 --> 01:58:13.119
the stables and the workshops, finally
leaving nothing in the city but its

01:58:13.119 --> 01:58:15.599
tombs.

01:58:16.800 --> 01:58:22.800
The ruins Khawla left on the mottled
flatlands of Tamhad appear and fade

01:58:22.800 --> 01:58:26.480
like the trace of a tattoo on the back
of a hand.

01:58:26.480 --> 01:58:30.560
There, my friends halted tall camels over
me, saying

01:58:30.560 --> 01:58:37.280
don't lose yourself in grief, man. Endure.
A man's soul flies to his throat in fear

01:58:37.280 --> 01:58:43.840
and he imagines impending ruin, though no
one stalks his evening journey, waiting.

01:58:43.840 --> 01:58:48.880
Death does not miss the brave -
- its slackened ropes around him, hand

01:58:48.880 --> 01:58:54.159
around the twisted coils.
A generous man quenches his soul while

01:58:54.159 --> 01:58:59.280
he is still alive.
I see the tomb of the hoarder, panting

01:58:59.280 --> 01:59:05.440
for his wealth, like the tomb of the
wasteful evildoer; both the same.

01:59:05.440 --> 01:59:11.760
Two heaps of earth were silent slabs of
hard, death stone piled up upon them.

01:59:11.760 --> 01:59:15.599
I see death choose the generous and the
noble,

01:59:15.599 --> 01:59:20.560
while picking over the best part of the
hardened, rich man's spoil.

01:59:20.560 --> 01:59:25.520
I see a life, a treasure,
shrinking every night,

01:59:25.520 --> 01:59:31.840
shrunken by days and time,
then gone.

01:59:36.480 --> 01:59:42.000
Thank you once again for listening to
The Fall of Civilizations Podcast.

